A Republican Strategy to Counter Obama’s Re-election
The leaders of the Republicans justify their policies with the need to combat election fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter to be a myth by reaffirming that election fraud in the U.S. is less common than the number of people killed by lightning strikes.
Republican lawyers have reported only 300 cases of electoral fraud in 10 years in the United States.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures partly undermine the democratic system of the United States.
Unlike Canada, the US states are responsible for conducting the elections in the individual states.
In this sense, the majority of U.S. governments have been promulgating new laws since 2009 that complicate the process of registering or passing the ballot.
This phenomenon has gained in importance after the November 2010 elections, in which 675 new Republican representatives were registered in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills were introduced in 2011 alone, restricting the exercise of voting rights in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also shorten the periods for premature voting, invalidate the right to register as a voter on Election Day, and deny citizens the right to vote for which a court file is available.
Before the 2006 elections, no U.S. state asked voters to show a photo ID card.
Indiana was the first state to make such a claim.
The Supreme Court of the United States confirmed the constitutionality of the Indiana Act in 2008.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have promoted bills in 34 states that force voters to show a photo ID.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal ID card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, i.e. 21 million eligible voters, do not have a photo ID issued by a government agency in their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such an ID.
However, often more than a hundred dollars are to be paid to obtain the required ID.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African-Americans, 15% of people with an income of less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over the age of 65, and 20% of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
This goes even further.
Students who are seen as voters who are increasingly voting for democratic candidates are not allowed to use their photo ID card issued by their institution in several states.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting associations, who vote more strongly for the Republican side, to use the cards issued by these associations for elections.
Before 2004, no state had requested proof of citizenship for the electorate.
Arizona was the first state to make such a claim.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove their U.S. citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting Hispanic voices.
It is obvious that two out of three Hispanic voters prefer the democratic party.
In addition, Republican legislators in eight states in 2011 promoted laws that abolished the registration of voters on Election Day.
In addition, you have limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to those voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, the campaigns for voter registration in the general elections of 2004 helped to register about 10 million citizens.
As a result of the measures adopted since 2009, the share of registration of new voters in 2010 has decreased by 17% compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators in five other states have passed laws aimed at shortening the period for premature voting.
For example, in the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of voters who voted in advance were African-Americans, although they make up only 13% of the state’s voters.
The same goes for the Hispanic population.
The latter represented only 11% of the voters, but 24% of the citizens who voted in advance.
By contrast, the whites, who represented 76% of the voters, made up only 46% of the voters who voted in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters have vigorously opposed the adoption of laws that restrict the registration of voters.
Several bills were blocked by the vetoes of democratic governors.
The U.S. Attorney General has intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, the new rules introduced in 2012 will undoubtedly make it difficult to exercise the right to vote.
The democratic critics denounce the party-political nature of the passed laws and see in them as a clear goal the influence of the results in the decisive states for 2012.
A 2011 report by the Brennan Center shows that those states that passed these laws make up 171 of the 270 votes required in the electoral body to win the presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these legislative changes to the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures partly undermine the democratic system of the United States.
Prostate cancer early detection: should the test be done or not?
The PSA test, in fact, sometimes shows incorrect results, with false negative or also false positive results that lead to unnecessary medical interventions.
This leads to a greater hesitation of the already undecided men for carrying out early detection tests.
Should the test be done or not?
We have obtained the opinion of two specialists.
In the studies conducted in the US, there were numerous interfering factors between the control groups, making it difficult to interpret these data and make clear recommendations.
Another study, this time from Europe, concluded that there is a difference in the mortality of patients with and without early detection.
This study also showed that following follow-up after 12 years, the likelihood of metastasis formation is 30 to 40% higher if no early detection has been performed.
Therefore, I recommend the test from the age of 50 or 40, if you have a direct relative who has already developed prostate cancer.
Men of African-American origin also have a higher risk.
The most important thing is to make the right decision as soon as a cancer has been detected.
There are cancers that are aggressive and others that are indolent.
The patient must really understand the extent of the risk of his cancer by showing him the possible options where prostate cancer can remain untreated if it does not impair the quality of life in the long run, and in these cases one is more likely to opt for active monitoring of the disease.
Today, many men who have been diagnosed with cancer do not receive treatment because their cancer is not aggressive and does not pose a threat to their lives.
They are suggested to have active monitoring and offer treatment when the disease progresses.
The criteria for deciding who should and who should not be treated are determined with increasing accuracy.
Therefore, I still recommend carrying out the test.
However, the most important thing is to talk to your doctor to determine if he should be performed or not.
In collaboration with the International Society of Urology, Movember has developed an instrument that enables the evaluation of the pros and cons of the PSA test.
