The Higgs boson analyzed
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson has caused a certain sensation last summer, and for good reason.
It is indeed believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted by the standard model – our best or “least wrong” explanation of nature and the behavior of matter – but has not yet been empirically observed.
But for the physicists, it is not yet completely certain that it is really the Higgs.
We know without the shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto, but data is still missing to be completely safe about it.
Nevertheless, let’s assume that it’s actually the Higgs, as there seems to be only a small risk of deceiving oneself, and let’s look at what it’s about.
There is an unavoidable law in this world that prevents two objects from being in the same place at the same time.
It is not possible to violate this rule - and do not try it too strongly as you will hurt yourself.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that such a law also applies to it: the Pauli’s exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time when they are in the same “quantum state”, whereby this “state” is broadly composed of some of its properties.
On this basis, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In a corner are the good citizens, who are called Fermione and who kindly obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the bosons move, an evil gang of anarchists to whom nothing is sacred - in any case not this principle, which means that they can indeed be in the same place at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratories (which by the way is absolutely amazing) these bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons that we will not treat here and the "power particles" through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
It must be emphasized here, however, that these bosons are not all such exotic creatures as one might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "light particle", which is the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
When a particle accelerates with an electric charge or changes direction, the electromagnetic field is "disrupted" at exactly this location, in a way like a pebble that was thrown into a pond.
This "disorder" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of force".
Stable field
The same goes for the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "disturbed" for this boson to show up.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must reach very high energies, a bit comparable to a frozen pond, whose surface could only be feared by a very large rock.
That’s why a huge particle accelerator like the CERN is required – the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a circumference of 27 km! – to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, it is not all particles and not all materials that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others do not - for example, a sheet of paper would never hold on to the refrigerator by itself.
And equally, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the others (like the photon) have no mass.
For what can all these researches be "good," Ms. Plamondon asks?
For science, they are used to review the standard model (SM), and they also allow physicists to accurately examine all the differences between the observations and predictions of the SM.
By the way, there are numerous physicists who eagerly hope that such deviations will be found, as the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and stuff some holes in the model.
It must be said that the latter still has great flaws, as it does not provide an explanation for gravity (ups!) and dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter of the universe (again ups!).
However, such deviations have not been found at CERN so far.
Impact
The impact of these researches on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there are none.
By the way, in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell labs did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle – who worked at the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who himself developed the first continuous-stroke laser (the first ones were pulsed) in 1962 – has already told us that the laser was initially considered more of a “laboratory play.”
You can imagine...
In addition, applications can also result from all the instruments that surround the research.
For example, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor during his work in optics in 1969.
Although it was not the original purpose, today this sensor serves all digital cameras worldwide as an "eye" and won him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will inevitably change our lives, but it does mean that you really can never know...
Palliative care - the best way to die... <0x7C> Le Devoir
With its Committee on "Death in Dignity," Quebec has recently discussed the delicate issue of end of life.
The debate must be resumed shortly, although a bill is being prepared.
However, there is still much work to be done in this important area.
Le Devoir tried to take a closer look at this.
A few weeks ago Mr. L. lived alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that devoured him had left him a period of two years.
"They gave me five years to live, I managed seven years," he said half-heartedly, lying in his bed in the palliative care home of Victor-Gadbois in Beloeil, where he had arrived the day before.
"However, it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for that," he says.
The disease does its job: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table in front of a delicious lunch, he resignedly agrees to let himself be helped with dinner.
Courageously, he even manages to smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medication, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is to cure my diarrhea because it is humiliating," he said.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"Over the course of our lives, we learn that a man is peeing while standing," says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois home.
Returning to childhood is an unacceptable humiliation for some.
"It depends on the person's ability to take a step back," he notes.
In the opinion of several people who work in palliative care, large events take place amidst these regressions.
Patients enrolled in the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home are all suffering from cancer.
You have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, they are no longer overwhelmed by the doctors and nurses who take care of them with so-called "healing" care.
For Ms. A., 89 years old, the worst fear is to die “consciously and by suffocation”.
But because of the disease, I really got to know my children.
“I have good children,” she adds.
“I don’t have any wishes in life anymore,” she says before accepting that a mask should be put on to help her breathe.
In the next few days, however, she expects a last visit from her son, who comes from Italy.
In the Victor-Gadbois home, a group of volunteers offer personal care and assistance with food intake.
Palliative care is used when there are no other options.
To make dying more enjoyable.
In Quebec, there is a bed for palliative care for 11,700 people.
That's very little if you take into account that one day we'll all die.
Here, life continues under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person is given oral care with brandy or pepsi, as desired.
Diabetics no longer have to control their blood sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer that died during the night.
This morning his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help relatives and patients alike," says Nursing Director Nathalie Savard.
In the home of Victor-Gadbois, there is no day like the other.
In addition to an old man of 93 years who enjoys the last family gathering in the yard and is well supported by his pillows, while striking in his honor, a young man of 36 years, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two young children, tragically dies after trying everything to survive.
“For six months, three to five beds have always been filled with cancer patients under the age of 45,” Martel said.
53% of patients admitted to Victor-Gadbois home come from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e. to a care designed to alleviate the suffering of patients when the latter have reached the final stage of their lives, both at home, in the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois home and the Society for Home Palliative Care in the Montreal area, are more or less exclusively specialized in the care of cancer patients.
It is precisely this great insufficiency in Quebec’s healthcare that causes several doctors specializing in palliative care to look forward to passing a law regulating euthanasia and assisted suicide with concerns.
Since October, a manifesto has been in circulation, signed by prominent palliative care figures such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, to express their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec’s healthcare system is not powerful enough to ensure that everyone has the right to high-quality palliative care before accepting death.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was in the emergency room for 14 days with great pain, without any measures being taken to relieve her.
I fear that patients only want to die because they don’t receive adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients, despite the worst prognosis, forbidding until the last day.
Hél<0xC3><0xA8>ne Richard’s chances of survival were already minimal when she discontinued heavy chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop treatment, she replied that she regretted giving up the fight, she told me.
But she told me I was at the end!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die thank the nursing staff for not fulfilling this wish after their pain has been alleviated by a palliative care team.
However, it must be clearly stated that palliative care is not omnipotent in pain treatment.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of palliative care of the Society of Home Palliative Care of the Montreal area, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to terminal sedation, which results in either sporadically or permanently putting the patient to sleep until the time of his death.
We can no longer pretend that we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the opportunity to resort to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not relieved all say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that doesn’t necessarily mean, “I want you to put me to sleep,” but “I want my pain to be relieved.”
