Bitcoin allows you to pay and sell without a bank
The opposite of the current monetary exchange based on central banks, identified transactions and processing fees between the parties involved.
In addition, as so often in these technologies, a political vision is tangible: the conviction that the current monetary system, shaped by banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, the Bitcoin invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym) is both a virtual currency (but convertible to dollars, euros, etc.) and a protocol for secure exchange such as BitTorrent, which allows the direct exchange of files.
With 15,000 computers on the network, about 200,000 transactions have already been recorded.
Some thousand websites accept Bitcoin as a donation or as a means of payment.
After Bitcoin’s price peaked at $30 ($23) in June 2011, it dropped to $2 five months later, before recovering at around $10 today (the prices are listed on the bitcoincharts.com website).
Nothing particularly impressive compared to world trade in real currencies or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes Bitcoin as “the virtual currency with the greatest success,” “competing with the dollar or euro,” and “similar to conventional currencies.”
Bitcoin is different from other types of virtual currencies such as the “credits” that are used to advance in a video game that you can win or buy (and sometimes trade back) by playing.
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, trade is controlled and handled by a central authority each time.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously depositors of the billing book, auditors, money issuers, as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two email addresses in the form of an email.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A number of the data associated with this transaction is electronically signed by a double encryption system.
In this way, the network can check the authenticity of the transaction.
Using the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the traded bitcoins are present in the billing book of public accounts spread throughout the network.
The crucial step is to enter this new transaction into this book.
This is done through a mathematical task that is started on the computers, with the winner, who is a sort of interim central banker, having the privilege of adding that additional line.
It is a fragmentation of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and unambiguous electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole thing is "hacked".
The goal is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
If this number is found, the other nodes can easily check if it is the right one.
The transaction is thus permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user wants to pay for cheating twice very quickly (less than 10 minutes) with the same money, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other would remain without a link because both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the task will receive 50 bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, this reward is regularly halved, probably before the end of 2012.
The Bitcoins in circulation are thus limited to 21 million, but divisible up to a hundred millionth, leaving a certain amount of leeway.
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with each improvement in computing power.
The life of the network has already had ups and downs.
The websites that provide services for Bitcoin were attacked and the Bitcoin deposits stolen.
“The vulnerability used does not affect the actual protocol,” assures Pierre Noizat, who has just introduced Paymium, which is a real-money payment company and the network uses Bitcoin.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering using this anonymous service.
However, cash also shows these shortcomings.
Major actors such as Wikipedia refuse donations of this kind.
They are accepted by others such as the WordPress blog platform.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the billing book and showed that nearly 80% of Bitcoins are not in circulation.
A "mega final sale" was launched in November.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” said Jon Holmquist, who works for the company Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book about this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
Its Paytunia system corresponds to a credit card (with real money) or a contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses Bitcoin to validate the transactions that are cheaper.
In addition, the owner manages his identity and can thus remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented by dealers, and the latter do not need to install new terminals or computer programs.
You just need to provide an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by a phone, says Pierre Noizat, who assures that he has thousands of users.
There is a general trend in which hierarchical systems are reconsidered in favour of more horizontally aligned systems.
“It will take some time for Bitcoin to prevail, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicts.
Incidentally, the ECB’s report proposes to reassess the various risks that are highly regarded today in the event of success of this currency.
We have moved out of Afghanistan.
And after that?
French troops have left their responsibilities in Afghanistan (Kapisa and Surobi).
NATO and the US are expected to follow at the end of 2014.
It is time for the Afghan army to retake possession of its territory, and for the Afghan people to decide their future without expecting anything from us.
In particular, we punished Afghan farmers by seeing them as terrorists.
And ourselves with our 88 killed soldiers, as well as the injured and injured.
The Taliban consist of foreign extremists, former leaders who have fled to Pakistan, but often also peasants who refuse an armed foreign presence, as in the time of the Soviets.
They want to defend their centuries-old and archaic traditions, even though jihadists, Pakistanis, Arabs, Uzbeks and Tajiks have joined them.
Tolerated, sometimes supported by local insurgents, the latter will no longer be there as Western countries become more discreet.
The withdrawal of the French troops from the base in Nijrab, which I observed from a hill planted with almond trees, which was financed by French loans, was done properly.
The truck and tank convoys flown over by helicopters have reached Kabul without being attacked.
As of the end of 2014, there will be no more influx of the Taliban into Kabul.
Since its irresistible advance from 1994 to 1996, conditions have changed.
At that time, Kabul was empty and the country was overrun by war due to the struggles of the various insurgent groups.
Their takeover of power was then seen as a kind of liberation and return to security.
The Afghan women have paid the price for the obscurantism of the farmers overwhelmed by the al-Qaeda organization, but their situation has not improved to date.
Former Mujahideen, the Afghan government and current Taliban have a common desire to keep women in a subordinate position.
The most important personalities of the anti-Soviet war came back to power in 2001.
They have turned into businessmen by confiscating government land to sell it as a construction land to refugees from Iran and Pakistan, taking advantage of the massive American subcontracting.
They were in disrepute, and most of them were not themselves involved in the fighting.
As I have heard in the campaigns, people want a government that is not made up of thieves.
Many young people want to leave the country, as well as those who were able to take advantage of American subsidies: the capital flight is considerable.
Young people are tired of war and its ideologies.
During their exile in Iran or Pakistan, they have had contact with the modern world and enjoyed its benefits.
About 65% of the population is under 25 years of age; Kabul now has 5 million inhabitants, which is one fifth of the total population.
In the cities, state schools are full of girls and boys.
These young people, who do not want to return to the obscurantism of the former parties or to the corruption of certain leaders, will have to provide jobs.
All, including the armed parties, are obsessed with mobile phones; television with its Turkish series, which represent a modern world, is watched everywhere.
There is an army now.
Are the authorities under whose command they will be considered legitimate?
Former commanders of the anti-Soviet struggle are already working to restore the militias in the province, which will escape the power of the central government.
Afghanistan, the land of the mountains with strong local identities, should have benefited from some decentralization by the example of Western nations, but by abolishing the office of prime minister, which has existed since the 1964 constitution, the US wanted to make it a centralized state with a strong presidential power.
President Karzai does not want foreign controls, especially on the occasion of the elections scheduled for April 2014.
However, his country has been dependent on foreign aid since the 1950s and long before.
Industries have not been rebuilt, functional dams do not exist and important irrigation systems have not been repaired.
Everything is imported; apart from fruits and vegetables, nothing is produced.
The private initiative is given priority.
In a country that was undermined by 30 years of war, state control of infrastructure would have been necessary.
The rumor has been spread that Afghanistan has immense mineral resources.
This reinforces the impression that the Western countries were only there to seize it.
Without energy to process iron or copper ore on site, or without means of transport for export over the mountains, mining is not possible.
The Chinese have almost left the copper mine of Mes Aynak, have international archaeologists (funded by the World Bank) make their excavations at the huge Buddhist site and remain the province’s main employers.
One day it will also be necessary for Afghanistan and Pakistan, which are largely dependent on imports and exports, to restore normal relations.
