The new cooperation agreement provides for the continuation of traditional aid: girls' and boys' gymnasiums, French Institute of Universities, French Institute, cooperation in the military, legal, medical and agricultural fields, support of the archaeological delegation.
Since 2009, a service of "civil-military actions" of the Ministry of Defence (Cimic), which was discontinued in 2012, has carried out numerous non-profit work and measures for the rehabilitation of agriculture in dozens of mountain villages, and has been carried out by a small French non-governmental organization to try to win the "hearts and spirits" and achieve the impossible task of reconciling aids and offensive actions.
These works, which required many local workers, have helped to suppress the uprising: irrigation, wells, drinking water, reforestation, fruit trees, soil protection and increasing agricultural lands.
What souvenir do we leave behind after military spending of two billion euros?
A much more modest budget will help improve local living conditions, which are very harsh in these valleys, often at an altitude of more than 2000 meters.
The embassy has received dozens of written requests for small agricultural projects from municipalities in the province of Kapisa.
In order for farmers to free themselves from the insurrection led by foreign groups, which according to their own statements is their wish, the continuation of less, more well-controlled and directly related civil aid would be necessary in their favor.
A Constitution with a Breaking Rod in Egypt
This is a new poker game by President Mohammed Mursi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever in terms of the Constitutional Declaration granting it unlimited power of attorney, it has decided to put everything on a map.
To everyone’s surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had granted this plenary two additional months for the completion of its work.
Egypt has now been relying on a provisional text that has been amended several times for almost two years, weakening institutional stability and leading to a legal mess.
This new initiative has only led to an even stronger division of the country.
For his opponents, the president persists in his "autocratic delirium" by continuing to "break his word" and "step the law with his feet."
On the part of its supporters, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time, forcing the brothers to renounce their intention to explain the text to the Egyptians section by section.
For the president, it is also a way to regain his public and democratic legitimacy as the protest rages across the country.
After reaffirmations in an interview with the American weekly show Time, Mohammed Mursi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote benevolently.
Especially since the Egyptian people are given an ultimatum with this resort to a hasty vote: "either you vote for my draft or I retain the unlimited power of attorney", the latter should supposedly come to an end after the adoption of the constitution.
85 mostly Islamist members of this constituent assembly passed the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of the liberals did not comply with the request.
Shortly before the Constitutional Declaration in mid-November, they turned their backs on the idea that they were unable to express their views.
Representatives of human rights organisations, religious minorities or civil society have acted equally.
11 people, deputy members, were added in all haste to achieve the decision-making capacity yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim brothers.
It is not surprising that the articles were mostly adopted unanimously.
Incidentally, commentators found it entertaining that the only difference of opinion of the day... was expressed at the time of prayer, as some members of the panel felt that the commuting clock of the Constituent Assembly was not accurate.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which attracted all the attention, remains ultimately identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, stating that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law."
The Salafist parties, for which the establishment of Islamic law is an important requirement, had the hope of replacing "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made stricter application possible.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is proof of their good will and their respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
The liberals, who see this only as a propaganda strike, reciprocate.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place via other articles.
In particular, they have Article 220 in mind, which grants the University of Al-Azhar an advisory function, in particular with regard to the verification of conformity with Sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is alarming, as "the persons invited to comment have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy whatsoever.
Here you can see the first signs of a theocracy."
The fears of the liberals are also fuelled by the fact that the next rector of this university is far less moderate than the current one.
“There is no concrete religious commitment at the moment.
With this constitution we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not Ulema, but academics who have been trained in part in the French system,” said Alexis Blouet, who writes a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
He acknowledges, however, that "there may be ambiguity with regard to Article 220, since the terms used are borrowed from the religious vocabulary.
In particular, reference is made to the "Fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence, Note d. Red.].
And in the future, the question could be raised of the extent to which civil judges are competent to decide.”
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is strongly criticized for the far-reaching powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another point of dispute: the powers of the army.
In line with the military's wish, the examination of the defence budget is not submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Similarly, there will be no ban on civil proceedings in military courts, as the associations for the defence of human rights have demanded.
The latter also share their fears regarding the text they consider to be a threat to freedom.
The blasphemy is maintained, and insults are now banned, which could have serious consequences for the right to freedom of expression, especially for the press.
In addition, no more article refers to the protection of women, underlines Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In their opinion, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to speak out on TV last night, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
The proponents of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists expect sacred sites, the navel of the world and a sea of brine
The Promised Land combines the glory of biblical truths, modern comforts and untouched nature.
AIF gives you the five main reasons to visit Israel.
Bend in front of the holy places
Visit the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all who bathe in this river receive God’s blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: the transformation of water into wine at a wedding celebration, walking on the water, the calming of the seastorm and fishing.
This is where Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
Most of the shrines are in Jerusalem.
Believers will follow the Path of Suffering or the Way of the Cross of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The path begins at the Roman fortress of Antonia, Pretorium, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the church of the tomb on Mount Golgotha, where the crucifixion site, the anointing stone and the tomb of Jesus are located.
Here, in the Christian view, is the navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of humanity.
The monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands at the place where, according to a Christian legend, the tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus grew.
In Jerusalem there is also the most sacred place of the Jews - the Western Wall, the remains of a temple that was destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
Traditionally, people of different faiths leave there papers with wishes that are then fulfilled.
Take a trip up the hill
The ruins of the fortress of Massada form the remains of the secret hiding place from enemies that Herod the Great had built for his family in A.D. 25.
They lie on a rocky wall in the mountains at 450 meters above sea level.
Only mountaineers can reach the ruins on their own.
Everyone else brings an aerial cable car to this historic summit.
In the north of the country, at an altitude of 1600 to 2040 meters, there is the famous ski resort Hermon, which attracts countless tourists during the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you can get there by a shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometers.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods lived on the mountaintop.
Visiting unique museums
There are almost 300 museums in this country.
With just one trip, not all of them can be visited.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be a visit.
Among them is the Israel Museum near the Knesset (Parliament).
There, ancient Qumran manuscripts or Dead Sea scrolls found in rock caves in the Judean desert are kept, as well as about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
There is a collection of works by Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Akko you can visit the museum in Bad Al Basha, which houses several rooms of old Turkish baths with sculptures of the then visitors and bathers.
In Caesarea, you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures of Dali and Rodin.
There are no museum guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are generally refused.
The fifth museum, namely the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most shocking chapters in history.
The most poignant section is the monument to the children, built to commemorate the 1.5 million children who were destroyed in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
When entering the room there is complete darkness.
Stars sparkle.
And the names of the Jewish children and the countries in which they died are resounding.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Doing something for health
The three most important recreational areas of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
At each of the three places there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Surprisingly, the Red Sea is also bathed in the winter months, as the water temperature there does not fall below 21°C and the air warms up to 23°C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and there is bathing all year round.
By the way, this unusual sea, located 417 meters below sea level, is the lowest sea in the world.
Its turquoise blue water has a high salinity and therefore wears even non-swimmers without problems on the surface.
The surrounding landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural salt brine) and medicinal sludge as well as for the treatment of skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and to calm stressed nerves.
Touching the mysteries of antiquity
These secrets lie in the old town of Tel Aviv, namely the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through this city was the famous sea route that connected Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to tradition, Noah built his ark right here, and Perseus saved here the beautiful Andromeda with which he lived a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to stroll through the narrow streets named after zodiac signs.
Fortune is said to be hold to all who touch the walls in the alley with their zodiac sign.
In Jaffa you can meet newlywed couples from all over Israel and even other countries at photo appointments.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theatre and conquer the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and residence of the Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre now hosts evening concerts and operas.
List of tourists
If you’re going to Israel, don’t worry about your poor English skills: About 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
The money in the trip you prefer not to take in euros, but in dollars, which can easily be changed into shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city you usually get by bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a highway and in Haifa the only subway line in the country with six stations that connects the lower city with the upper city.
In fact, it is an underground funicular.
A trip within the city costs 6 shekels, regardless of the means of transport, which is enough including a change for a trip of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated in Israel on Saturdays.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transport is at rest.
And on Sunday morning, the working week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and restaurants, only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, seafood, shed-free fish and food that includes both milk and meat products.
Instead, you have the choice between different dishes with ham and beef, soups and desserts (made with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, various sauces, fried balls made from pureed beans and peas (falafel) as well as fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
For this there are many well-nourished cats who stroll comfortably and untroubled through the streets.
In the evening you can even see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
The cats like busy places and don’t say no to treats.
Depending on the brand, a rental car costs between $37 per day (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
The insurance costs an additional $15 per day.
And bike rental costs 15 shekels per day.
Entrance tickets to museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
In numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most adventurers and recreation seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the United States and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists came to the Promised Land, an increase of 51% compared to the same period in 2010, before the cancellation of the visa requirement on February 9, 2011.
"The Great and Mighty" Leads to Moscow: Migrants Save Money for Language
While MEPs and civil rights activists discuss the benefits of the law on binding language tests for migrants, criminals are already dealing with counterfeit certificates
Every year, 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, Saint Petersburg and other cities in Russia.
Most of them are the citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money for the maintenance of the families remaining in the home.
On 1 December, a law came into force that required every migrant worker to take a test that certifies knowledge of the Russian language.
Until now, this regulation only applies to migrants who want to work in the services sector, in the municipal housing industry and in the retail sector.
However, the tests will become mandatory for all guest workers over time, according to the Federal Migration Authority.
Not only language tests, but also tests in Russian history and the basics of legislation.
Language skills must be demonstrated both for obtaining and renewing the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
Also exempt from this law are persons who received their training certificates and diplomas before the disintegration of the USSR in 1991.
Purpose, problem and protection of rights
The entire examination body will be under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute for the Russian Language, the Russian University of Friendship of Peoples, the Moscow State University, the St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
The migrants can take the tests in all cities; already more than 160 corresponding centers have been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by members of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Authority.
Civil rights activists, on the other hand, asked the press several times before the law came into force: What does it actually bring?
What changes does the requirement to have language skills bring, both for the Russians and for the guest workers?
Above all, migration agency spokespersons are concerned with reducing the number of forced labourers.
"Many are now talking about protecting the rights of migrant workers," said Viktor Sebelev, head of the Federal Migration Agency's representation in Tajikistan.
However, your rights must be protected before you leave.
Only organized recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Problems are encountered by migrants without a job, education, language skills and medical assessment.
Sebelev is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably meet people with evil intentions who will put him in a dark, narrow barrack under the pretext of help, where he will endure with dozens of months of his own without food and documents and work 12 to 14 hours a day.
We receive a lot of complaints from our migrants.
"In the home, you are promised one, and upon arrival, you will be cheated, their passports will be taken away and not receive the promised salary," confirms the head of the labour migration department of the Tajik migration agency, Tolib Schwaripow.
Don't grumble, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics, who want to earn their money in Russia, admit that they can not only not master the language of the target country, but can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault, but rather the evil: only a few Turkmen, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford a reasonable primary education.
Because in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone to buy them decent clothes, shoes and school supplies.
As a teenager, these children immediately seize the first opportunity to make money.
"It's difficult without language skills," they admit.
“You feel humiliated and inferior.”
Civil rights activists emphasize the following important aspect regarding the law.
Only migrants with legal status must take the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, most of the guest workers continue to reside illegally in Russia.
"Welcome" or "Access prohibited for unauthorised persons"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic hurdles and, of course, linguistic difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be done quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
The staff of the Russian police know that our documents are mostly fake and we are not registered, and this results in cases of blackmail.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," the Tajik Umed Hushkadamov told journalists.
"Just don't shy away from cost of false papers"
Already on the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of the migrants can be fake.
Some counterfeit certificates certifying the completion of the language test have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Agency.
The counterfeit papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not get them for nothing: every migrant who hoped to be able to save himself from the tests paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
That’s more than twice as much as the cost of the official test: it costs a migrant worker three thousand rubles.
The most important immediate task is to protect the system from corruption so that the certificates cannot be easily purchased, both officials and civil rights activists agree.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise guest workers who fall through the test the first time they get time for a basic language course.
In addition, newcomers without language skills are offered jobs in areas where active communication with people is not necessary.
Interior Ministry Ignores Illegal Weapons Market
Proportion of legal weapons in crimes extremely low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior is planning to tighten up the gun laws for private gun owners.
The authorities react to the recent events: injured in shootings at weddings and seven dead in the assassination of Moscow lawyer Dmitry Winogradov.
The police want to ban the wearing of non-lethal weapons in public and raise the age of possession of firearms from 18 to 21 years.
The proposal was supported by the chairman of the Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Jarowaja, and promised that the amendments to the arms law would be submitted to the Duma shortly.
Not everyone is satisfied with the fact that the Russian authorities want to fight the problems by "attracting the screws".
An open letter has been published on the Internet, the authors of which – representatives of various arms associations – demand the authorities to refrain from “senseless exacerbations”.
The percentage of crimes involving registered weapons is very low, said the criminal lawyer, Vasily Lesnikov, the Russian service of the BBC.
According to the Interior Ministry’s statistics, 142 crimes involving the use of registered weapons were committed in 2012 over the course of six months, while a total of 1,168 thousand offences were recorded for the same period.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that a tightening of the law for private gun owners will not prevent criminals from using the black market.
According to the authors, you can find every possible weapon in Moscow for little money.
Meanwhile, the Interior Ministry stresses that the proliferation of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The weapons reach the black market through several channels.
There are five such main channels, tells a former Colonel Viktor Baranez, who worked for ten years in the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of a website that accepts gun orders
The first channel is the army or military, i.e. weapons stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
“The weapons were stolen by both the Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves,” Baranez said.
On the second channel come illegal weapons that are stolen by criminals.
Baranez explains that these include weapons that have been stolen from both the police’s armaments and directly from law enforcement officials.
Other illegally sold weapons come from military weapons camps.
In many military camps there were often explosions.
"There is evidence that some cases were arson to cover up the lack of weapons," the former military official said.
According to Baranez, the arms manufacturers also make a contribution to the black market.
“Today, there are countless private armament factories that do not stand up to international competition and, therefore, throw away arms on the black market, for example in Moscow,” the expert reports.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
Especially many guns and rifles come from poor countries such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is a production of its own, sometimes handicrafts, as well as a mafia that organizes the smuggling," the former military official explains.
Where did the weapons come from?
Experts calculated the proportion of each of the five channels in the supply of illegal weapons to the black market.
In 2011, a report was published by the Center for Problem Analysis and State Administration.
The experts analyzed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, criminological literature and publicly available data on weapons portals.
The majority of the illegal weapons come from the army and legal protection authorities, according to the investigators.
Half of all the weapons on the black market are there due to the "debt of those responsible who have to deal with weapons in their work," the report said.
According to the researchers’ data, 17% of weapons come from conflict areas, 14% are due to theft in weapons production, and 5% are from illegal excavations.
A sales consultant at a gun shop who does not want to be named assures that weapons found in illegal excavations have long since been bought by no one since they are outdated.
According to him, it is more common for merchants to obtain supplies in a weapons warehouse.
A gun, for example a TT-type pistol, is purchased via a ensign.
The weapon is displayed and passed through the fence.
"The dealer brings the gun to the city and sells it there for 900 euros each with two magazines," he says.
“Police, of course, know about everything and, therefore, if they cannot comply with the plan to detect crimes, make periodic check purchases from merchants who offer illegal weapons,” the sales consultant adds.
"Like in the luxury shop"
Buyers and sellers find each other most often via acquaintances.
I had looked at websites and blogs when someone became aware of me and suggested coming to the station "Begowaja" where a person would wait for me to bring me to a certain place where we could then negotiate the price.
I only learned the price of the gun there.
