Over the past few days, there have been massive protests across the U.S. against low wages in Walmart stores and restaurants of popular fast food chains such as Mc Donald’s, Burger King, Taco Bell, Wendy’s and Kentucky Fried Chicken.
No one can yet predict whether the protests will continue to swell or whether they will soon get out of the air again.
The protests are supported by trade unions and several left-wing non-profit organizations.
In addition to increasing the modest wages of simple Walmart and fast food employees, the protest organizers pursue the goal of founding trade unions.
So far, this sector of the economy has hardly been organized by trade unions.
46 cents a year?
The protests began last week after Thanksgiving, on so-called Black Friday, where sales were held in the U.S., attracting millions of customers, sometimes leading to handcuffs.
On that day, some Walmart employees, of whom there are 2.2 million worldwide, dropped their jobs and, together with trade unions and left-wing activists, raided the chain’s branches targeting low- and middle-income people.
Walmart sells all products, from diapers to hunting rifles and car batteries to vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
The goods in the Walmart stores are on average between 8 and 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
That’s why many of the low-paid Walmart employees only buy at their own workplace.
The prices and product range made Walmart one of the largest companies in the United States.
According to critics, Walmart can often sell the goods so cheaply only because the employees are poorly paid.
The latter also complain about heavy working conditions, for example missing forklifts or handheld scanners.
Participants in the protests on “Black Friday” demanded wage increases and expressed their anger over the fact that the contribution to the company’s own health insurance had risen from $30 to $100 a month.
A typical Walmart employee who earns $9.5 an hour could not afford this increase, they said.
Researchers from the California University in Berkeley prove that if the company raises the average wage to 12 dollars per hour, it would cost Walmart 3.2 billion dollars.
That’s about 1.1% more than they are now donating for wages.
If Walmart were to shift wage increases completely to customers, each purchase would cost them only 46 cents more in the future.
For them, this would be a yearly surplus of only 12.39 dollars compared to today’s surplus spending.
Proponents of Walmart are pleased to note that there were only protests in nine states and these did not cause any losses to the company.
Black Friday lasted in its store from 8 a.m. on Thursday to midnight the next day, and in that period Walmart sold about 5,000 items per second.
In total, Walmart cash registers carried out nearly 100 million transactions on Black Friday.
The company's spokesperson, Dan Fogelman, claimed in an interview on the left-wing Huffington Post website that a total of "less than five" Walmart employees had dropped the work and the protest action was merely "another PR trick" by the union that organized the protests.
"Free cash!"
The protests continued this week in New York, where their targets were not Walmart stores (which are not desirable in this progressive city and therefore so far inexistent), but McDonald’s and other affordable restaurants.
McDonald's says the company sells billions of servings, and yet you are not granted sick days, and you are not paid for your honest work!
Jumaane Williams, Member of the New York City Council
Currently, the minimum wage under federal and New York legislation is $7.25 per hour.
In fast food restaurants, the minimum wage is gradually raised, but not too high, and on average, their simple employees in New York get $8.90 an hour.
No one deserves less than she does in this expensive city.
How it is possible to get along with so little money in New York is incomprehensible to me.
There was once a time when almost a quarter of all U.S. teenagers were behind the counter after school at McDonald’s, but the teenagers were still living with their parents.
Hardly anyone saw it as the main source of income or planned to stay there for longer.
Now in interviews with McDonald’s employees, I constantly meet people who complain that they have to cope with this pay and sometimes even feed their children.
On the other hand, there is a commentary in the Wall Street Journal’s forum, whose author notes that it is irresponsible to have children if you don’t know how to feed them.
Participants in the protests, which began on Thursday at 6.30 a.m. in front of McDonald’s on 40th Street and Madison Avenue, demanded that cashiers and chefs from fast food restaurants receive a minimum wage of $15 an hour, which is more than a doubling of the current minimum wage.
They continued to demand the formation of trade unions in the fast food industry.
The U.S. law prohibits corporate governance from standing in the way of this goal and warning or dismissing union members.
On the other hand, corporate governance does not make it easy for them.
However, the establishment of trade unions in the fast food industry is also difficult for objective reasons.
The most important reason is the high staff fluctuation.
Dissatisfied
There were loud protests that day in front of many other fast food restaurants in Manhattan.
The highlight of the protests was a lunchtime meeting in front of McDonald's in Times Square where some local Democrats spoke, including City Councillor Jumaane Williams, who said, "McDonald's says it sells billions of servings, and yet you're not granted sick days, and you're not paid for your honest work!"
The protesters were also supported by other prominent New York Democrats, for example, mayoral candidate Bill De Blasio, who said that "we should jointly support the fast-food employees so they can receive a fair wage and achieve the economic prosperity that every New Yorker deserves!".
According to the New York Times, this was the largest action of its kind in the history of the U.S. fast food industry.
However, only a few hundred people were on the ground, not all of whom are employed by far in the fast food industry, where tens of thousands work in New York.
It is not yet clear whether the spark of these protests will mobilize entire masses.
"The brain can only be moderately overwhelmed so far"
The theme of augmented reality, popular with fans of modern technologies, has recently been typically perceived by the lens of a special pair of glasses.
First, Google presented a working model at its annual conference in the summer, then in November it was announced that Microsoft had also filed a corresponding patent.
Speaking to the leader of the group for interactive 3D technologies at the Microsoft lab in Cambridge Shahram Izadi, however, it becomes clear that the glasses for the company’s scientists were only a transit station.
It excites the ability to manipulate virtual objects in the air with bare hands and create virtual open spaces.
- Please briefly describe what research your group is doing.
- We deal with the interaction of man and machine, but want to expand the limits of this interaction.
So far, humanity has largely stuck in the phase of working with pixels on flat screens, which are sometimes touched as well.
However, we want to anticipate 5-10 years and anticipate the radical changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are an advance, and nowadays no Xbox is sold without Kinect anymore, as everyone is interested in motion control.
- What can we expect in the future?
- Although Kinect has brought the interaction to a physical level, a lot is still happening on the flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information (the system receives more data) could be improved, the output not yet decisive.
We try to change this, working on real three-dimensional representation systems based on different technologies, including projections.
We need to release the computer world into our physical world and make it more tangible.
For this, however, it is necessary that not only the user, but also his environment is recognized.
Then we could add virtual objects to the real world much more easily.
And first of all, we should get rid of these stupid virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
It’s popular, but isn’t it overrated?
- It is certainly not the all-purpose solution, because it raises questions about privacy, because you do not always want to inform everyone around about its actions and intentions.
Actually, any kind of interaction with computers is good, but each in their particular niche.
For example, in the field of controlling objects in public places, we worked on a project in which we experimented with short and scarce gestures instead of elaborate gestures.
The gestures were not recorded by the object camera, but by a bracelet that recorded the movements of the bones and muscles.
It is still relatively large, but could theoretically be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But overall, the future belongs to mixed control types, such as gestures and language.
- How's that?
- For example, we'd ask you to give me this can?
They say it and point to it at the same time.
- Normally I'm just saying it.
- Oh, that would be very hard to see.
- Does this mean that you want the user to adapt to what a machine can and cannot afford at any given time?
- Not necessarily, but it's about a mutual approach.
I think that we will have to work in the near future on developing new sensor types that will allow us to capture people’s reactions more accurately.
These can be laser sensors, for example, because they offer good resolution in depth, which is very important.
- What demands do you make from your work with the Xbox Kinect sensors on modern cameras?
Is there a lack of resolution, depth or something else?
- The current generation is basically a good starting point for our work in the field of three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, 8 megapixels at a speed of 1000 fps would not be bad.
But the main thing is not the megapixels themselves, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
From this point of view, all current technologies are not good enough for us, as the developers of the algorithms have more work to do.
Not only the resolution along the X- and Y-axis, but also along the Z-axis must be taken into account.
The speed and number of images per second are also important.
The movements of humans are extremely dynamic and frankly, the current 30 fps are not enough, especially for gestures.
In our laboratory in Redmond, Stephen Betishes developed a touch sensor with a controllable processing delay between 1 and 100 milliseconds, with today’s commercial sensors closer to the second value (60 to 100).
Not everyone understands how much this affects the interaction between man and machine.
For my work, I needed exactly such a device, only without touch control and with more images per second.
- Shouldn't the number of cameras be increased?
- Kinect currently works with three "cameras", one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the second is a receiver for the reflected signal.
And the third camera is actually an ordinary RGB camera.
It is not used to calculate the object depth.
More cameras could possibly solve the problem...
Or increase the problem, as more calculations would be necessary.
It would be nice to have a flexible, Kinect-like system where we could play with different camera inclinations to see how this helps us in the three-dimensional determination of a position.
- If I remember correctly, unlike Google, Microsoft did not present his glasses to the public.
Don’t you think that with regard to the application of advanced reality technology in everyday life, the glasses have the best prospects?
- Of course, it is not pleasant to always hold a smartphone in the raised hand while on the go, but I think the best option would be a "changing" augmented reality, where we could switch from glasses to smartphone via a cloud,
The glasses are a personal gadget and therein lies their strength (private can only see you), but at the same time their weakness, because an extended reality using glasses prevents you from working together with others on virtual objects.
- Imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holograms in the air is not only accessible to Tony Stark from Iron Man, but also to normal mortals.
There is a problem that critics of this idea often point out: there is no tangible reaction!
Your hands feel nothing at all.
What answers does your group want to give to this objection?
- In my lectures, I often mention that augmented reality is the seventh breakthrough in human-machine interaction.
I think the eighth breakthrough could well be the integration of tactile perception.
An interesting method is currently the use of the second hand as a somewhat unusual projection support.
She perceives pressure excellently!
But there are also technologies that are actually aimed at giving the "pictures in the air" something handy, for example, the interference of some directed ultrasound beams at a certain point where the finger is, creates a feeling that is currently as weak as someone blowing over the palms.
There are also ligaments for the wrist that act on the nerve endings in the fingers, also this is a potential direction.
- Did you try to outwit the brain?
Do you think it feels what it should feel when it sees something?
- That's a good idea, so we haven't tried it yet.
Here is another task that we will have to deal with for a long time, namely to make a person who is physically in a closed space believe that he is instead in an open, practically infinite space; here we are working on concepts with treadmills (other than in gyms), moving platforms and large balls.
So far, the brain is only moderately overwhelmed, and there are still many busy years ahead of us.
This is precisely what makes the work in the field of virtual reality so appealing for a researcher: With many topics, we are only at the beginning.
