Birth in space
Earth in danger.
Global warming or collision with killer asteroid.
Caravans of spaceships with Earthmen on board are looking for a replacement planet.
To save humanity, the important question is how can we reproduce in gravitylessness or on the replacement planet?
In my opinion, there are not many choices.
In fact, there are only two real planets that we could at least hypothetically inhabit.
"Mars and Venus," says the research associate of the Astronomical Sternberg Institute Vladimir Surdin.
However, while the conditions on Mars are comparatively life-friendly, there is a temperature of 500 degrees on the surface of Venus.
Life would only be possible at great heights or in the orbit of Venus, i.e. in space.
The researchers first dealt with the question of reproduction in space with regard to the flora.
Already half a century before, experiments with plants were carried out.
The fourth generation of orbital-bred peas did not differ in the slightest from Earth’s species.
It was followed by the breeding of insects, more precisely of tiny fruit flies (Drosophila), in orbit.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent into space to explore how weightlessness affects the development of embryos.
It develops a normal chick.
But then the problem begins.
"The problem is that the chick must be able to stand on its legs and begin to move," explains the laboratory director of the Institute for Medical-Biological Problems RAN, Vladimir Sychev.
Without a solid surface, the chicks swarmed wildly.
Ten hours later, the instincts of the newborn completely dulled.
The chicks did not react to light and sounds.
Four days later, they simply died.
"Twice we let chicks hatch and then set the whole thing up because it is simply impossible to work with them there," says Vladimir Sychev for the failed experiment with the chicks in space.
The last breeding cage with animals flew into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in spring 2013.
However, the biosatellite "Bion" will only contain same-sex species.
There was an experiment with rats that were already fertilized into space.
In principle, nothing special was found.
"This was just with the biosatellites, but again it was just a single experiment, and the research needs to be continued," notes Vladimir Sychev.
After the landing, the space rats were given offspring.
The problem of reproduction directly in space has not yet been solved.
The task is difficult.
Animals that are torn from their natural habitat simply cannot follow their reproductive instincts.
In contrast to animals, humans could do that in principle.
Homo sapiens is capable of abstract thinking and can create a similar emotional background.
Out of ethical considerations, such experiments are not carried out.
Women have been flying into space for 50 years.
The greatest risk was in Tereshkova.
The most valuable thing that humanity possesses is the female organism.
Our seagull flew away, and no one on Earth could have answered the following question: Does it survive space flight?
Will she be able to give birth to a child after this flight?
"Finally, no one answered this question," says space veteran Wachtang Watschnadse.
In June 1964, just one year after her space flight, the first female cosmonaut, Valentina Tereshkova, gave birth to a daughter.
The father of the child, Andrijan Nikolayev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second woman in space, Svetlana Sawizkaja, who was in orbit twice and even performed work outside the spacecraft, gave birth to a son.
Nevertheless, there remains a risk.
We have very few cosmonauts, where after long flights everything went well and they got healthy offspring.
"The more, the more dangerous it is even on flights into orbit," concludes cosmonaut Waleri Polyakov, hero of the Soviet Union and hero of the Russian Federation.
Yet humanity must look for new ways in biotechnology, radiation protection and the generation of artificial gravity.
The hydro lab in the cosmonauts' preparation center is a mandatory station during flight preparation.
Here in a floating state, the cosmonauts gain routine for working in open space.
The water represents weightlessness.
Even though adults find water pleasant, it is a strange environment; but infants perceive water as a natural element.
It is as if the little Ichtyanders were bearing witness to the fact that life on land came from the ocean.
There is a connection between the fact that a child is in amniotic fluid for about 9 months in the mother’s belly, and that it can then become more easily accustomed to water.
In principle, this is logical, since from birth to the first swim only 2 weeks pass.
"That's too little time to forget something," says baby swimming instructor Marina Aksenova.
So, while weightlessness is a much more natural condition for a newborn child, the woman cannot do without gravity.
In the state of weightlessness, the abdominal and pelvic muscles recede enormously quickly and thus the ability to squeeze the child out decreases.
All right, let's bypass the birth-initiating aids.
For example, birth could also take place in a special chamber to squeeze the child out.
"But what happens then?" is the not insignificant question of Waleri Polyakov.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravity.
Without feeling the earth’s formation, the organism cannot train the skeleton and muscles.
In orbit, a newborn child cannot be put into a training suit like an adult.
He will simply lack what is essential to his life.
"This experiment, which we are doing together, namely the birth of a child in a foreign environment, will lead us to give birth to a disabled person, a completely inappropriate person," predicts Igor Pestow, head of the RAN's Bioethics Commission on Medical-Biological Problems.
So far, the birth of children in space is merely a theory.
At some point, however, it becomes a reality when the Earth’s inhabitants in their spaceships break up to a distant planet that will be the home for their offspring born in space.
