Otherwise, they wouldn’t have any kind of cooperation with our agency, would they?
With regard to Czech legislation, how important was the amendment of the Procurement Act to your authority, do you feel any impact?
In view of the fact that this amendment is only in force for a short time, it has not yet had an effect on our tests.
Since our checks take place retrospectively, you have to expect a certain delay here.
So far, we are more likely to feel the impact in the preparatory phase of future controls - for example, we have introduced the new control tool "Detection of risks of uneconomics" and with it almost 14,000 public contracts will be examined and analyzed - here, of course, the changes will have an impact as thresholds change, the conditions for certain types of tenders have been modified, among other things.
Do you see the adoption of this law rather positively, or is the system burdened with further bureaucracy?
I think that this law is definitely a step in the right direction and I hope that this assumption is confirmed.
However, the problem may arise that the rules become "strengthened" and can no longer be adhered to.
Under the previous rules, persons subject to audit are accountable to the institution (for example, in the case of an operational regional policy programme, the Regional Council) to the effect that any non-compliance with the public procurement law is a violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense to make the law even more stringent?
I don't think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse the system, and not punish those who have committed a form error that does not affect the actual decision-making process.
Such a system merely puts the bureaucracy under even greater pressure.
Where's the way out?
First of all, let’s say which path is not effective.
The prime minister recently said that the ODS would not burden the entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called "black system" - what exactly does that mean?
Is the black system banned or allowed?
A law must have its validity, and if something is prohibited by law, then the president of the government cannot simply come and hinder the control office, whose duty is to control the observance of the law.
He can say, "We change the law and allow the thing," but he can't say that we're pretending to be nothing.
The Procurement Act contains relatively strict rules on the formal execution of certain transactions - and this is correct for the protection of public competition.
On the other hand, it is also tragic if the bidder with the best offer is excluded solely due to form defects.
The law will never be perfect, but it must be applied correctly - and that is what I think is missing from us.
