<0xC5><0xA0>imon Ornest: At our concerts we want to gather positive energy
What do you think is going to happen in less than a month?
This is one of those disaster reports that we people like to start on.
With our band The Tap Tap, we are more likely to make fun of it and say that we are the only band in the world that can accumulate enough positive energy to stop or prevent the end of the world.
In December, you will also realize a unique project with three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you introduce the project to our readers?
This is a nationwide fundraising event that we have been planning for two years.
For this, we want to use the marketing potential of the Mayan calendar, whose end is forecast for December 21 at 11:10 a.m.
The day before, i.e. on 20 December, three concerts will take place simultaneously from 21:00 in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
The end of the concerts is said to be about the time when the Mayan calendar ends on the Pacific island of Kiribati, which is in a time zone around 12 hours ahead of us.
From whom did this idea come?
Originally probably from me, then we designed the idea together with our graphic designer Honza Augusta.
Not only do we want to gather enough positive energy to prevent the end of the world, but we also want to think together with the public about the state in which we are handing this world over to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar, we have also developed a unique collection of shoes, t-shirts, bags and keychains against the end of the world, with the purchase of which people can also support us via www.e-tap.cz.
The band The Tap Tap has also recorded, together with other performers, the so-called anthem against the sinking of the world, entitled "The sinking of the world".
The anthem is already very popular on YouTube today. Will it also be resounding on the benefit concerts?
Of course, and last but not least, provided that everything works and the end of the world does not take place...
The anthem will be sung by all performers at all three concerts at the same time.
In addition, the hymns are broadcast live together in a direct connection from Czech TV.
The lyrics of the hymn come from Tom<0xC3><0xA1><0xC5><0xA1> Han<0xC3><0xA1>k, who also plays the main character of Jesus in the video clip, also Xindl X sings with...
How did you come to work with both?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, which is related to the fact that we realize many charity events and concerts...
We strive to involve these people intensively in our projects.
It has been shown that most people are interested in working with us and have fun with it.
What is the purpose of the proceeds of concerts against the end of the world?
For the establishment of the barrier-free educational centre Studeo, at which we have been working for six years together with the association Tap at the Jedli<0xC4><0x8D>ka Institute.
The students of the Jedli<0xC4><0x8D>ka Institute are regularly supervised by lecturers who help them with various leisure activities.
Since the students themselves do not have the means to visit the lecturers, we would like to help them in this way.
As part of the completion of the Jedli<0xC4><0x8D>ka Institute, a separate building is to be built, into which we will then move with this project.
At each concert, several groups and performers perform.
What criteria did you choose?
We wanted to put together a program that appeals to all generations, including children.
In Prague, for example, Chinaski, Support Lesbians, Illustratosphere with Dan B<0xC3><0xA1>rta, The Tap Tap, Mari<0xC3><0xA1>n Bango and Ji<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xAD> Such<0xC3><0xBD> perform.
You can find out more on the website www.kpks.cz.
Are similar "big events" planned for the future?
In May we perform for the first time at Prague Spring, and also for this concert we prepare an interesting program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to perform at the Czech House in New York, and I personally - if we are already in the USA - would like to combine this with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your foreign plans are not very small, so far you have already appeared in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
However, The Tap Tap is a group of people with disabilities.
How do you manage these trips logistically and organizationally?
It’s not as bad as it appears at first glance.
Five of our members are wheelchair users, i.e. the wheelchairs must be transported in the luggage compartment. In addition, of course, we have to carry a lot of instrument cases and other luggage...
Nevertheless, it has always worked out without any problems so far, <0xC4><0x8C>SA and British Airways were always very well prepared for us, that I have sometimes wondered already.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
Through your travels abroad you have a comparison of what it looks like in the individual countries with accessibility, how to deal with disabled people there, etc.
How have you experienced these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities where everything works better than ours, we were just in Russia witnessing that in the East everything is still in its beginnings.
Compared to Prague, Moscow is absolutely not suitable for people with disabilities, where it is still uncommon when someone is travelling in a wheelchair alone in the city center.
It is not even a matter of course that you leave a wheelchair user in the elevator, for example.
Fortunately, there are also associations that try to point out the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what respect do we need to catch up with the more developed countries?
There are still a lot of things we hang out in behind...
It should be noted, however, that an improvement in the situation always depends on the efforts of those affected.
In London and Madrid, it is quite common for people with severe disabilities to move independently in public spaces, go to the museum, use toilets, etc.
However, it is not common for a larger group of disabled people to actively participate in social events, in which we are a little ahead of the West with the band The Tap Tap!
Respect for the public and accessibility is one thing, but only when important athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers come from our ranks will things really start to change.
So far, these are only individual cases of particularly strong-willed personalities.
The Tap Tap is very popular right now, but if we go back a few years, what motivated you to start a band in 1998?
At that time I started as a supervisor at the Jedli<0xC4><0x8D>ka Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in dealing with something intense.
And since I myself am a musician and play saxophone, I founded a music company together with a colleague.
Well, and over time, as our moderator, L<0xC3><0xA1><0xC4><0x8F>a Angelovi<0xC4><0x8D>, used to say, something has gotten out of control (laughs).
But the band has only been known in recent years, or am I mistaken?
It’s true that working with well-known singers helped us; we also started to actively promote ourselves.
We have come to realize that if one does something and this is not visible to the outside, one’s own performance does not exist in a sense.
Thanks to the EU funding, we can also afford good readers, high-quality equipment and the like.
Was it your goal to get it this far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning, I felt the potential that things could be handled differently.
In the show business today, one often copies the other.
This is logical in its own way, as all new things are considered with caution and only accepted after a long time.
There are few really unique things, and I dare to claim that tap tap is part of it.
The first impression that the viewer usually has is of course compassion; this is only natural...
But this pity is absolutely superfluous, because people with disabilities are not lonely and abandoned beings we should regret.
They are people who can live a full life and develop, provided they have the necessary means to do so.
I always say that if people with disabilities succeed, this is not only a progress for them, but for the whole society.
Was it also helpful for this success that you are a strict boss, as you hear from many people?
If you want to do something good, you must not compromise on many things and you must also demand a certain discipline.
However, I think this is perfectly normal.
Some come to us with romantic ideas, and if they find that they have rehearsals twice a week, have to complete preparatory phases and spend a lot of time on concert tours, then the enthusiasm of many quickly goes out.
This is how it works everywhere, in every band that wants to work seriously and achieve something.
The Tap Tap currently has 20 members.
How many of them have been there since the beginning, i.e. since 1998?
Only one: L<0xC3><0xA1><0xC4><0x8F>a Angelovi<0xC4><0x8D>.
We're an open group. People come and go. You can't stop that.
Anyone who has the will and the desire to participate is always welcome with us.
