Poland and Space.
Last week, Poland was accepted as the twentieth member of the European Space Agency at a Council of Ministers meeting of the member countries of the European Space Agency (ESA), making it the second member country from the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became an ESA member on 12 November 2008).
Poland began a close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
Poland’s journey into space began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish cosmos enthusiasts were already engaged in space travel, but they did not always come up with understanding.
I recall, for example, A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld’s lecture at the Warsaw Observatory on December 6, 1933, at which the author presented thoughts from his pioneering work “The Entrance to Cosmonautics”.
However, the ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the listeners cold, and after years <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
<0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch, donated by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch, in 1934 for "Eingang zur Kosmonautik".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space travel.
In Polish journals he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski’s world-renowned contribution to the development of space travel was appreciated, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the Earth’s remote side of the Moon was named after him.
Already in 1925 a railway draisine was built in Poland, for which a rocket propulsion was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used for starting or braking the Draisine.
The information on this comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-powered missiles.
The research was conducted by the Kom<0xC3><0xB3>rka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
It can be seen from the documents that the research had reached the stage of practical testing.
The research was then interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937 the design of a photoelectric hunting rocket by Ing. Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski appeared in the specialist press, and the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects dealt with the military use of the rocket propulsion.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of missile technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy).
The Committee was established in 1937, but after two years of activity, its work was terminated from the beginning of the war.
Further articles on space travel appeared after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Agency (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne) in the Polish press.
The first mention of this society takes place in 1954 in the November issue of the journal Problemy, in which four extensive articles are devoted to space travel.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal for the establishment of a space company.
At the time, there were already the first satellite technology projects, and it was foreseeable that exploration of space would have a future.
Already from its beginnings in 1956, the Polish space company PTA sought to join the International Federation for Space, which was founded in 1951, and indeed the PTA became a regular member as early as the autumn of 1956.
The following year, the first PTA chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902-1959), became deputy chairman of the International Federation for Space.
He held this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been instrumental in the development of the extremely successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The missile with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and did not weigh quite 5 kg.
Later, an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959 began flight tests in the B<0xC5><0x82><0xC4><0x99>d<0xC3><0xB3>w Desert with the two-stage RM-2 rocket.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach an altitude of up to 14.5 km and be used for observation of high-altitude winds.
In 1962, however, further development was discontinued.
The successor to the first RM rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Of this rocket, three types were developed (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a transport space of 0.4 litres, Meteor-1B over 0.34 litres and Meteor-1C over 0.62 litres.
The maximum altitude for all three types was 37 km.
From 1965 to 1968, the Meteor 2 rocket was developed at the Aviation Institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
After that, the versions Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth noting that Poland joined the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, followed by the creation of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
Poland also participated in space exploration with Soviet satellites as part of the Intercosmos programme, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after the Czech Vladim<0xC3><0xAD>r Remek.
The repeal of the non-profit work law is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the non-profit work law.
This decision sparked a lively discussion in the public eye.
It is certainly interesting to look at the problem from a broader perspective.
The liberally oriented economic systems in the EU and in the globalized world are based on the principle of unregulated economic competition.
In the end, this means that the individual economies are in a permanent conflict with each other.
The reason for this is the principle of free trade and the free, unrestricted movement of private capital, which goes hand in hand with unrestrained financial speculation.
Due to the large differences in the value of labour (wages), there are price tensions.
This term refers to a condition in which the manufacturer attempts to survive economic competition by importing favourable goods by "undercutting" competition in order to gain a greater market share and increase its profit.
On a large scale, this means for most companies to relocate their production abroad or buy cheaply there, or to abandon their business. The result is high unemployment in countries with comparablely high labour costs.
Since private capital bears no social responsibility and thus no responsibility for the unemployment it causes, government spending necessarily increases.
This situation is reinforced by the fact that the employers are absolutely reluctant to pay their taxes and thereby compensate for the social and economic damage they cause.
This situation is generally known, so that concrete statistics are unnecessary at this point.
The ruthless practice of private capital creates in the individual economies a situation in which governments are forced to compete with each other in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population and thus attract foreign capital into the country.
In other words, governments deliver their own populations, regardless of the social consequences, to private capital.
This is expressed in particular in amendments to applicable laws.
The aim of these measures is to force the own population to accept the dictate of private capital, especially in the field of wages.
This is done, on the one hand, by economic compulsion in the case of long-term unemployment, on the other hand by the circumcision of workers' rights.
The result is growing poverty, as well as ever greater differences between rich and poor.
For several years now, there have been public food outlets in Germany for poor people who are no longer able to feed themselves through their own work.
The number of people affected is already in the millions.
In the course of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, there are regularly cases in which workers receive such a low wage that the state must increase their income to the minimum of living.
Such a scandal was also uncovered in the case of aid workers employed in the German Bundestag.
The austerity measures of virtually all EU-Southern countries will undoubtedly result in the same state where people are forced to emigrate under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of their social level (as was the case in the 19th century), or for a hunger wage on the margins of society, hoping that at some point private investment capital will flow into the country.
The question arises, of course, where does this capital come from?
When it comes from another EU country, poverty merely migrates from one country to another; or the capital remains the same, because in China, India, Brazil, Turkey, Morocco or Egypt, or in Africa at all, the employees work for a fraction of the European wages.
This applies to all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and media claim to the point that the state is not allowed to participate in its own economy with capital, and that the planned economy leads to an economic catastrophe.
Private capital insists narrowly on its position that the state must not intervene in the economy in a steerable manner.
Then you have to ask yourself whether private capital does not influence or even direct politics and thus the entire state in its own selfish sense.
Here is the clear answer: yes.
The proof of this is the existence of a virtually omnipotent and ubiquitous lobby in all states.
The result is a desperate situation in the field of corruption, mutual preference, a legislation in which practically everything is punishable, but nothing is punishable.
In Germany, the situation is such that a State Ministry, due to lack of finance, commissions private legal companies, closely intertwined with industry, to draft draft laws.
These bills will then be passed in the Bundestag.
All violence then no longer comes from the people, as the Western constitutions proclaim, but from strong financial groups who prefer their own interests.
Clearly, liberal democracies are now rapidly entering a situation as described by Appian in his work on the crisis of the Roman Republic in the days of Caesar and Pompey: "The state has long been in disintegration, and the offices have been occupied by force.
Against lubrication, by illegal slimming of advantages or with stone and sword.
The corruption grew unrestrained, and the people went to the polls with already purchased voices" ... "People of character did not apply for offices, so that the state, as a result of this decline, had no consul for eight months" ... "It was already really begun to talk about that the only medicine in this difficult situation was a sole rule, and that a strong man had to be replaced by César's democracy at last, but Appian thought of the strong man in this.
As it turns out, today’s society, as in ancient times, is founded on the ruthless preference of one’s own advantage, without paying attention to the interests of society as a whole.
Private capital is by its very nature incapable of recognizing and enforcing the advantage for society as a whole.
The result, today as at the time, is an unprecedented decadence of elites who are not in the least striving for in-depth reforms.
We must therefore look for the cause of the emergence of fascism and communism in the reckless liberalization of economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
From today’s standpoint, the demise of these regimes in favor of liberal democracies can be seen as a certain pause in which the next round is already taking place.
Particularly catastrophic is the fact that today’s elites are in complete ignorance of the future possible losses of hundreds of thousands of lives, the humanitarian and social disasters we are already witnessing today, and the crimes against humanity as we know them from the past and the past.
The repeal of the non-profit work law is not a solution here, at least not a permanent one.
Under pressure from global and European economic competition, the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to push down the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore systemic.
The only solution is targeted political-social reforms that increase the state’s participation in the economy, increase the influence of citizens on the government, and weaken the monopoly of private capital in society in favor of the state.
