Argo: When It's Worst, Call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of demonstrating Islamist students occupied the U.S. embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
For their release, they demanded the extradition of the overthrown Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the United States after the revolution, who had maintained patronage over his regime for decades.
There was no positive way out of this situation for the American government - it could not afford to throw the shah overboard, as this would have massively damaged the trust of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, in Iran, where the revolution resulted in the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to enforce the release of the hostages.
It was a heavy blow to the reputation of the United States, and the subsequent fiasco in the violent attempt at hostage liberation only made things worse.
The captured diplomats were finally released after 444 days after negotiations had been mediated by the Algerian government.
The fate of the hostages caused a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiments at home.
The debacle in Iran significantly contributed to the defeat of Jimmy Carter against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo by director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that gave the United States a small partial victory.
Immediately before the embassy was filled, six embassy employees managed to escape.
This ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to bring the refugees out of Iran, helping them with an extravagant story to cover up their true identity – they travelled with Canadian passports disguised as members of a film staff who allegedly visited filming locations in the country for a science fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan developed by the exfiltration expert, Tony Mendez, also required Hollywood's collaboration.
For the camouflage to become credible, articles about this film project appeared in specialist magazines, press conferences were held, and the fictional production company had a real office.
The details of this operation have been kept secret for a long time. The film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck’s film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand, he is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time also a so-called "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful hussar piece such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
As a result, the mood levels change in the film - on the one hand, the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence, iconic contemporary photographs are shown, and there are no major differences in the film version of the same situations).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood, which come ironically and slightly oversized.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men dressed in suits at the meeting table, on the hallways, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has made a remarkable restart of his career with this film.
A smiling actor has become a respectable director, and even as an actor, he is no longer the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the Krimi Kein Kinderspiel (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the thriller Stadt ohne Gnade (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck’s first film not to play in the director’s hometown of Boston.
The feel for the atmosphere of the place was one of the features that made this director’s previous films stand out from Hollywood’s standard.
Affleck, however, also proves this feeling in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film play in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that really took place - the entrance sequence of the storming of the message is very impressive in its clarity, yet conveys the feeling of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when the story moves somewhere.
Affleck and his team also achieve a similar effect in fictional scenes (the wrong film staff on a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story does not offer many exciting scenes in the cinematic sense.
However, with the few, he works quite successfully, sometimes helping out with reality - which then doesn't always look so elegant (the scenes where the impending crisis at the airport in Tehran is averted by a phone call in America, or also the chase on the runway, seem somewhat artificial).
The weakness of Argo is its all too wide dispersion, which is due to the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their characters would have earned more space, and thus they are far from alone in the film.
Affleck’s film loses some traction, a film that can be followed with a certain interest and that can gout the design and the retro style reminiscent of a thriller from the 70s.
However, it is hard to arouse enthusiasm.
However, it is sufficient as a reminder of a piece of history alive to this day in a certain way and as a proof of how exaggerated the notions of the omnipotent and omniscient intelligence services are.
