The MVRDV architects prove that the true adventures are not only in the mind - on the example of Spijkenisse and the recently built Bücherberg - 2 photos
"I find the building funny, it looks futuristic, and finally there's something interesting to see," says Lisette Verhaig, a passer-by on the roadside.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT technician in a nearby large company, says, "Well, it's nice, the house."
I wonder why we need a library today.
Everyone has internet, iPad and e-books.
No one goes to one of these old-style libraries voluntarily today, right?
Spijkenisse, a sleep city that hardly needs to be visited at the gates of Rotterdam, is a strange record holder.
The 80,000-resident community has the lowest educational rate in the whole of the Netherlands.
In order to counter this stupid circumstance, it was decided a few years ago to contribute to general education and to recreate the seven fictitious bridges depicted on the euro notes as beautifully brushed reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And so the city fathers realized that there was only one way to master statistics: a library had to come!
Winy Maas of the Rotterdam architecture firm MVRDV, master of the great-know-for-the-bar diagrams and producer of funny, often cynical buildings, took the matter with usual serenity and appeared for the competition hearing in 2003 with five books under his arm and a grin on his face.
And while the jury was still stunned looking around and shrugging his armpits, the naughty Maas piled his exquisite gift in size to a pyramid and finished his actionist-backed speech with the words: "Dear city community!"
So this is it, my suggestion for the Book Mountain of Spijkenisse, for the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30-million-euro mountain is piled up.
It is part of a revitalization project, which also includes underground parking, supermarket, post office and a few adjacent residential and terraced houses with a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, the Bücherberg was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project is also nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
This is the faceless small town retreat, which to date had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and a staggeringly ugly town hall, behind whose white facades one would be inclined to suspect a dairy factory in order to enrich a piece of contemporary architecture.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in the history of its existence.
The long way to the book
The first impression: Book ring orado under cheese bell.
There is a lift that leads through the middle of the mountain massif, but the true pleasures of space and reading open up as the topography climbs on foot.
The glazed interior is bright and clear, the fired clinker floor and the elegant street lights speak unmistakably the language of a public city square.
The urban ambience is perfect.
People are already looking for park bench, dog and football-playing boys and girls.
And everywhere books, books, books.
“Normally the bookshelves stand along the facade, and in the middle lies a large, dark room, which is usually uncomfortable and impersonal,” says Winy Maas.
We have turned the classical room configuration upside down and the reading area from the inside out.
The interior of the Bücherberg is cleverly used: in the middle are offices, internet library, chess club, environmental center and house technology center.
A special joy are the black bookshelves, which are sometimes wall panelling, sometimes breastfeeding, sometimes stair railings.
Optics, feel and smell are foreign.
Even ingrained architects and civil engineers shake their heads over the unknown building material.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials here," explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, at the request of the standard.
And so we came across a suitable waste product from agriculture in a Frisian farm one day.
For many years, a millimeter-thin plastic fleece has been used as a root base in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands.
This is cheap and time-efficient.
The thin textile lasts for one, two seasons, after which it is ripe for the bulky waste.
For the library, the fleece - for the first time in these quantities - was pressed to four centimetres thick plates.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous, load-bearing material that smells like new cars and like sports shoes.
After 105 steps you reach the summit.
At the end of the almost 500 meter long hike, the Literaturcafé not only rewards you with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and stuffed ficus trees.
They provide atmosphere, but above all the right humidity in the literary mountains.
Donations for the new soul
"You wouldn't believe it, but this house is a showcase project in terms of ecology despite the many glass surfaces," Trouborst says.
It is heated and cooled with geothermal heat.
Although the Bücherberg is under a glass fall, even on sunny days the sun shines only briefly inside.
The wide wooden glue binders, which stand transversely to the glass fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade, serve as shading and capture much of the sunlight.
The indoor climate is very pleasant.
The rest is done by fully automatic roller blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the initial skeptic from the IT industry, was already daring his way into the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was there too.
And also the TCM teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who even describes the Boekenberg as Spijkenisse's "longest overdue soul".
The reason: At the opening a few weeks ago, each resident was invited to donate a book from his personal collection.
For the time being, the optical gaps in the not yet fully stocked library - currently 70,000 pieces - are to be filled.
The concept has gone up.
The shelves are filled up to the top.
“Nothing is worse than a half-empty library,” says architect Winy Maas.
"I think, thanks to our invitation, every resident now has a certain relationship with this new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
And if it is only for ornament.
With this, MVRDV has succeeded in the royal discipline, which is called identity foundation in the technical jargon.
Spijkenisse has written literary history.
No matter how young and uneducated she may be.
This is finally a starting point for identity.
