Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the most important sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and trippers (gonorrhea).
Common viral STIs are HIV, human pappiloma viruses, genital herpes or hepatitis.
Felt lice and scabies belong to the parasitic STI.
Who are the main groups affected?
Syphilis and trippers are especially common in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute estimates that at least four out of five cases of syphilis reported in Germany are transmitted through sexual contacts between men.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia infections, trichomonads, candidiasis (fungus), trippers and human pappiloma viruses are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The spread of HIV is comparatively low among heterosexual adults in this country - nevertheless: Around 20 percent of HIV new infections account for this group.
Among adolescents, chlamydia infections are much more common than in other populations.
According to European surveys, three-quarters of all infections affect young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
In addition, human pappiloma viruses are common in adolescents.
How has the number of infections evolved?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to reporting.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis infections has more than doubled from 1697 diseases in 2001 to 3698 diseases in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has been declining since 2007.
In 2011, there were about 2,700 cases.
That’s about a tenth less than the year before.
What are the symptoms of a sexually transmitted disease?
Infectious diseases can cause ulcers in the genital area, discomfort during urination, discharge, abdominal pain, as well as blisters or warts.
However, they often do not cause pain or other symptoms and therefore remain unnoticed.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but do not provide 100% protection.
In some cases, pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be passed on through lubrication infections and close body contact.
Therefore, experts recommend regular examinations, especially with frequently changing sex partners.
Diagnosed early, most STIs can be cured and late consequences can be avoided.
