This suggests at least one newly added article: In all matters relating to Sharia, the Al-Ashar University must be consulted, the most important Islamic institution in the country with great radiance in the entire Sunni Islam.
That doesn’t have to, but it can mean that the clergy oversees the legislation, which would de facto result in the disenfranchisement of the judiciary.
A lot in the draft is a matter of interpretation
Also problematic: the civilian military jurisdiction should continue to be maintained.
These courts served during Mubarak’s reign to oppress oppositionists.
After the dictator’s fall, up to 11,000 civilians were in military detention.
The state should also, as it says in the draft, "protect the true nature of the Egyptian family" and "promote its morality and values."
This is legally so blurred that state institutions could even control the content of film art and literature with the help of this article.
In plain language, this means nothing more than censorship.
No article explicitly states equality between men and women.
For this, another forbids insulting or slandering the Prophet Muhammad and his messengers.
But what an insult is and how it should be punished remains unclear.
Likewise dubious, the wording suggests that the "insulting of people" is forbidden.
Is there enough caricature of the president or a joke at the expense of a legal scholar?
It is a matter of interpretation, as is so much in the draft that Morsi is present for signature and, according to his words, will be presented "very soon" to the Egyptians for a referendum.
“The revolution has returned.”
The opposition has been forming for weeks against the superiority of the Islamists.
Tens of thousands gathered in unfamiliar harmony on Friday evening at Tahrir Square in Cairo, vowing to bring down the Charter before it can enter into force.
“The revolution has returned and we will win,” said Hamdin Sabbahi, third-placed president.
Nobel Peace Prize laureate and former head of the International Atomic Energy Agency Mohamed El-Baradei stated that the draft constitution belongs "on the garbage mountain of history".
Via Twitter, he accused Mursi’s supporters of wanting to lead a “coup against democracy”.
“If he calls the referendum, we will go to his palace and overthrow it,” said opposition leader Jasser Said.
"We are not tired yet, the blood of our brothers is not yet atoned," Egyptian media quoted opposition politician Chaled Ali as saying.
And several judges announced they would not want to oversee the referendum, which would invalidate it.
"The Koran is our Constitution"
The well-organized Muslim Brotherhood, for its part, blew to counter-demonstration, but not on Tahrir Square, but after a mass prayer on the other Nile bank in front of Cairo University.
Many veiled women and supporters of the Salafists took part and shouted: "The people demand the application of God's law."
They demanded of Mursi, "Cleanse the land!" and said, "The Qur'an is our constitution."
A battle for supremacy over the symbolic Tahrir Square, where everything began, would probably have conjured up civil war-like conditions.
Mursi’s supporters obviously didn’t want to risk that.
The Muslim Brotherhood declared that both the opponents of the draft constitution and the supporters had spoken out loud and clearly.
Now is the time to let the people at the ballot box decide in which direction the country should go.
A majority for the Islamist draft is considered safe.
"The word 'human rights' doesn't even appear"
Hafez Abu Saeda is furious about this forced constitutional process, which should have been going until February and involving all social forces.
The 48-year-old human rights lawyer and chairman of the Egyptian Organization for Human Rights (EOHR) defended the Muslim Brotherhood when they were in prison or on trial under Mubarak.
Not because he would share their worldview, but because human rights are indivisible to him.
For this he was beaten, convicted, imprisoned.
“And now the word human rights is not even in the new constitution,” he complains in a conversation with the “World on Sunday.”
Mursi's expansion of power to all three powers in the state had the lawyer resigned.
These measures are blatant violations of democratic rules and will lead Egypt into a new dictatorship.
"Instead of strengthening civil society, the president de facto repealed it," Saeda laments.
But without civil society organizations, democracy cannot work.
Saeda feels left alone, also by the international community, who considers the ideological battle of direction on the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and tension.
That could be revenge.
A protester on the Tahrir warns: "You are nurturing a monster that you can no longer control."
Rakfisk from Norway: Is this the most nasty fish in the world?
Norway’s five million inhabitants enjoy one of the highest living standards – not only in Europe, but around the world.
Could the country’s secret of success have anything to do with the local appetite for pretty nasty fish?
Take a selection of overripe cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a pile of dirty, damp sportswear.
Leave them there for a week.
You have to imagine the nose-deafening smell of Rakfisk, one of Norway’s great delicacies.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
There is snow here, spectacular landscapes - and that persistent smell in the air that just doesn't want to disappear.
Rakfisk is salt-sprayed trout, which is fermented in water for up to a year, depending on how stinky you would like your fish to be.
When the darkness comes over the country in Norway and the weather gets colder, Norwegians flock to a festival here in Fagernes dedicated to this, now, really very captivating specialty.
"You eat it raw and then flush it down with a glass of Aquavit," says Havard Halvarsen, who actually works in the local fire station, but also organizes the festival as a so-called "Rakfisk-General".
People around us eat small fish cubes and consume large amounts of alcohol.
"Many people like the Aquavit more than the Rakfisk," says Havard.
The spirits can displace the smell.
I'll have a few snacks.
If you avoid bringing the Rakfisk near the nose, it is not bad - like sushi, which has a pretty long bus ride behind it.
Rakfisk is the product of a very different, much poorer Norwegian epoch when there were no cooling options and fish was soaked in airtight saltwater barrels in autumn.
In the deepest winter, it was then removed after long fermentation and - undoubtedly with the help of alcohol-damped senses - consumed.
A generation ago, thousands of Norwegians in search of work were forced to leave their country and emigrated mainly to the United States.
Today, the population is growing rapidly – more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by a thriving labour market, high wages and comprehensive health care.
Even from Sweden, the old rival who was not too long ago far richer than Norway, immigrants flock.
Rakfisk is regarded as something important – as an essential, albeit strictly smelling, part of Norwegian history.
It is one of the more expensive dishes that you can buy here.
But actually everything here is expensive - a small glass of beer or a sandwich costs proudly 10 euros.
Norway doesn’t often make it to the world press, and most people don’t seem to bother.
Here one still hates to call Anders Breivik by name - that racist right-wing extremist who shot 77 men, women and children last year.
Instead, we refer only to the “July 22 incident”.
Norwegians struggle to accept that someone in their peace-loving country is capable of such brutal murders.
Since the early 1970s, the growth of one of the largest oil and gas industries in the world has been the main responsibility for Norway’s present-day wealth.
“But oil isn’t the only reason we’re doing so well,” says Anna, our waitress, who distributes the round trays with ripe rakfisk and embodies the Nordic ideal with her long blonde hair and stinging blue eyes.
We are, as they say, a prudent people.
Your English is just like most people here.
We're not very polite, we don't like bragging.
Norway has handled its oil wealth very carefully - a large part of the industry's revenues are invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
When, in the years leading up to the global economic crisis, everyone threw money around them that they didn’t own at all, Norway held its purse tightly closed.
"As long as we can ski in winter and go hiking in summer, we are happy," says Anna.
"And of course eat rakfisk," she adds with carefree laughter.
I stand in the snow and get ready for another dish - I've had enough of Rakfisk.
Such a moose burger is definitely something else. The juicy meat is mouthing me.
But in the evening, the stink fish is on the menu again.
The hotel I’m staying in is one of several venues that organize a Rakfisk dinner where guests can vote for the best – or perhaps the most challenging – fish.
There is a live TV circuit to a fly-clad showmaster surrounded by plates with Rakfisk.
The spectacle is similar to the Eurovision Song Contest.
"What score do you have up there in the mountains for the best fish, Thor-Jürgen?"
"Here's our points, Havard".
You are clapping and laughing.
A man falls from his chair, possibly overwhelmed by the aquavit.
But maybe it's the strict haze of the whole fish.
Mexico's Enrique Pena Nieto faces a difficult start
As Mexico’s future president, Enrique Pena Nieto, prepares to take office, Will Grant of the BBC analyzes the challenges ahead and the mixed feelings of his people.
Currently, traffic in Mexico City is particularly poor.
Even on better days, this city is always congested, but on Monday a steel ring was erected, blocking several important traffic routes to the capital and causing chaos on the streets.
The aim, however, was not to disrupt commuters on their way to work, but to prevent protesters from reaching Parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico’s new President Enrique Pena Nieto will receive the presidential tie and take over the leadership of the nation.
He is faced with a complex task.
Under the outgoing government of Felipe Calderon, Mexico has been able to prove itself economically well, but the country is in the grip of a drug war that has already cost 60,000 lives in the last six years.
“My government is committed to reducing violence,” Pena Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama at the Oval Office earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy to help us achieve this goal.
Before joining the U.S. president, Pena Nieto served as governor of his home state of Mexico.
In this densely populated, vast part of the country that surrounds the capital, opinions about the new head of state are shared.
A direct man
In the remote small town of Valle del Bravo, for example, people like to remember him.
Residents of the resort attribute it to the development of tourism and the construction of infrastructure.
To reach the city, you can drive on one of the highways that Pena Nieto had built, which is a big improvement over the fragile, bumpy roads that once existed here.
Plaques with its name also hang outside a modern sports centre and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We expect real and lasting changes from him," said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, who works as a congressman for the party Pena Nietos, the PRI.
In particular, as far as security and the economy are concerned, we hope for an interesting and real change that our country so desperately needs.
After 81 years in power, the PRI was replaced by Vicente Fox in 2000.
Congressman Olvera admits that after 12 years outside the Los Pinos presidential palace, the party has high expectations of Enrique Pena Nieto.
The accusations of the opposition, the new president lacks substance, he rejects.
He is a very direct man, very committed and has big plans for the country.
He is an excellent statesman, but above all he is also someone who can listen.
But on the other side of the state, not many people share this view of their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast to the cobbled streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
The place is hidden under highway junctions and in many ways represents a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the community are of crucial urban nature.
Earlier this year, the military was called in to fight the drug gangs operating in the neighborhoods, and violence against women is a particularly acute problem.
On a patch of land near a large landfill, the bodies of dozens of murdered women have been left alone in the past two years.
During the tenure of Governor Pena Nieto, over 1,000 women were murdered in the state of Mexico – a statistic that even surpasses that of the city of Ciudad Juarez, which is notorious for its violence and the murders of innocent women.
The critics of Pena Nietos believe that he has at least not adequately addressed the problem of women’s murders during his tenure.
But in the worst case, his government closed its eyes to the problem.
In a concrete building, typical of the declining neighborhood, Irinea Buendia struggles with the tears when she shows me photos of her deceased daughter Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of the events, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
But her family believes that she was murdered by her partner.
"When I arrived at her home, it seemed as if her body had been washed," recalls Senora Buendia.
There were signs that she was beaten, and the corpse stiff had already been used.
While her mother tells her story, from the wall a picture of Mariana looks down on us. It is attached next to a cross bearing a single word: justice.
But this, according to the family, has been denied to her so far.
The authorities treated me as if I were a chatterer, a troublemaker, a nerd.
They want you to simply accept their judgment and keep your mouth shut.
"But that's not possible if there were so many shape errors and failures," she says.
When President Pena Nieto receives the presidential tie on Saturday, he also assumes a great responsibility.
Tens of thousands of Mexican families have been affected by violent crimes over the past six years, and the new president has promised to take special care of this problem during his tenure.
"I hope that as president he is the same as he was governor," says PRI Congressman Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
This is what the families of the victims in Ciudad Neza are most afraid of.
Prosecutors claim Bradley Manning did not complain about abuse
Prosecutors contradict Bradley Manning’s allegations that he was abused in prison
The hearing deals with Manning's time in the military prison in Quantico, Virginia
The defense seeks a rejection of the charge due to harsh detention conditions
The U.S. Army Freedman is accused of having stolen thousands of confidential documents
The prosecutor’s office on Friday tried to find that Army-liberated Bradley Manning – accused of revealing the greatest confidential information in U.S. history – missed several occasions to complain about the ill-treatment he allegedly suffered in military detention.
During a cross-examination of Manning's during a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Maj. Ashden Fein explained that records of weekly visits made by prison officials during Manning's nine-month prison term in Quantico, Virginia, had no complaints whatsoever about his treatment.
A day before the cross-examination, which was held as a result of a request by the defense to reject the charge - Manning had already been sufficiently punished by the hard time in detention - Manning had declared that he had considered suicide in prison.
The U.S. Army intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The material was then published by WikiLeaks on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed Manning as the source of information.
In the hearing on Friday, Fein and Manning went through the forms that officials had filled out after their meetings with Manning during his detention at the Quantico Military Prison, where he had sat under increased detention conditions from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When Fein asked him about the forms on Friday, Manning admitted that he had judged the treatment by his guards as "excellent" and the treatment by the institution as a whole as "very professional".
The forms, Fein said, did not contain any complaints about abuse, although officials had directly questioned Manning about his treatment.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concerns orally and that the officials had discussed them with him and indicated that they were dealing with them, but that they had not been recorded.
"They wrote (after discussing the concerns) 'No problems', and that didn't necessarily mean I didn't say anything at all," Manning said.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment when he met with a committee in January 2011 to investigate the suicidal thoughts he mentioned on a form a few months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during this meeting was to lower his observational status for "prevention of injuries."
The military said it had assigned him this restrictive status - which is one stage under the risk of suicide - for his and the protection of others.
"I wanted to convince employees that I was doing well, and get rid of the observational status to prevent injury (...) in order to achieve a higher quality of life in my view," Manning said.
Manning said on Thursday he was arrested and transferred to Kuwait, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to the Quantico Marine Base Prison in Virginia in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and once became unconscious due to the heat.
Not knowing what was going on with him or in the outside world was a burden.
"My world has shrunk on Camp Arafjon, on this cage," Manning said Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
When he was transferred to Quantico, Manning spent most of his days in a small cell – at least 21 hours and often more than 23 hours – and without company.
He was only allowed a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, clothes and his glasses.
Manning said he tried to keep moving, because during the day it was forbidden to sleep or lie down.
He always had to sleep with light that entered his cell from the outside.
When he turned around at night and guards could not see his face anymore, he was awakened to turn back.
In January 2011, Manning's lawyer formally appealed Manning's treatment.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
On Friday, Judge Manning also asked about an accusation he had made in his statement on Thursday - for example, he had to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico for one night and had to stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners during a morning count.
Manning had stated that he had never had the opportunity to wrap himself with his blanket during this count.
At the interview on Friday, Manning stated that he had concluded on an order from his guard that he should drop the blanket he could have covered himself with, but he admitted that no one had asked him to do so.
On Thursday, Manning had testified that he was forced to sleep naked the previous night, and had previously tried to show an official that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning had told the official that he could have used the waistband of his underpants or flip-flops to hurt himself, but did not.
That night, Manning said, his underpants, flip-flops and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take his detention experience into account and drastically reduce his sentence should he be convicted in his trial in the military court, which is scheduled for early next year.
The defense has stated that Manning will plead guilty to minor offenses, while other charges deemed too extreme are to be challenged.
The hearing is scheduled to continue this weekend, and the prosecutor's office is expected to justify the conditions of detention.
The Pentagon maintains its position that Manning has been detained in accordance with the provisions applicable to all inmates held under the highest security measures in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include favoring the enemy, unlawful publication of intelligence information on the Internet, transmission of national defense information, and the theft of public property or documents.
If he is found guilty in all charges, he will face a life sentence.
My Mexican-American identity crisis.
Many people are forced to leave Mexico due to the lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to blame the emigrants – they remind them of difficult times, he says
Navarrette believes Mexican Americans are trapped between two worlds
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I had just crossed the hall and had arrived at the passport checkpoint when my senselessness spread inside me.
Signs referred to two queues: one for "Mexicanos" ("Mexicans"), another for "Extranjeros" ("Foreigners").
I stood there for a few seconds, unsure what to go to.
I grew up in Central California and have been called “Mexican” all my life.
An ethnic abbreviation - just as my friends in Boston call themselves "Iren" or my friends in New York call themselves "Italians".
Later, I decided to go for "Mexican-American".
But this was Mexico.
And in my grandfather’s home there was no need for shortcuts or hyphens.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish, at least well enough to assert myself in this language at both ends of an interview.
But I don’t have the vocabulary of a native speaker, and I don’t get rid of my American accent either.
So I took my American passport and put myself in line for Extranjeros.
I was thinking about that moment this week when future Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
On the agenda were all those issues that one expects when the heads of these two countries meet: immigration, drugs and trade.
Pena Nieto was also keen to talk about the growth of the Mexican economy, which is one reason why Mexicans today are equally likely to stay in Mexico instead of emigrating to the United States.
He wants to ally with the United States and Canada and create a North American trade bloc modelled on the European Union.
And Pena Nieto swore to continue the war of Mexico against the drug cartels, even though he did not mention any details in this regard.
Mexico’s relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never wasted a single thought that the United States invaded Mexico in 1848, forcing the country’s leadership to give them more than half of their territory.
But for Mexicans who think in centuries and not in minutes, memories of this event are not to be overlooked.
So as soon as a U.S. government official makes even the mildest criticism of Mexico, you hear complaints about how Americans are oppressing the sovereignty of their neighboring country, in the Mexican press and among the country’s elites.
And the children of Montezuma go on the war path.
And yet Mexico’s biggest challenge, in fact, lies in the relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States.
Want to talk about resentment?
There is more than enough.
Mexico has winners and losers, people for whom the country offers opportunities, and others for whom it does not.
The only reason so many people of Mexican origin live in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is because at one point in our family tree, a person – perhaps a parent or grandparent – was not offered a chance in Mexico and migrated northward.
And in most cases, this person corresponded to a profile - dark-skinned, uneducated, from a poor village, etc.
We are the descendants of these people, and our loyalty is to them.
Not Mexico.
And while we may now have lived the American dream, attended good schools, and received good jobs, we must never lose sight of the American dream we live—not the Mexican one.
Our identity may be blurred at times, but as far as our loyalty is concerned, this is not the case.
This clearly applies to the United States.
In addition, we are aware that many members of the Mexican leadership don’t like us.
This is based on reciprocity.
They see us as a reminder of a humiliating defeat and look down on us because we are not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our ties to Mexico will never be strong enough.
In their opinion, our existence is a symbol of failure.
If our families hadn’t failed in Mexico, they wouldn’t have left.
And then we wouldn’t see ourselves trapped behind the silk curtain—with a pleasant life in the United States, but somehow lost.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally immigrated to the United States as a child, reminds me that there are tensions between Mexicans and Mexican Americans because Mexicans have a clearer idea of who they are – and Mexican Americans take it ill.
While she is an American citizen, she sees herself as part of two countries.
But many Mexican Americans I know have the feeling that they don’t belong to one country or the other.
We love the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
One enjoys the best of both worlds, but is not rooted in either.
In Mexico, we are seen as Americans.
And in the United States, we are seen as Mexicans.
As I should learn during my journey, there is something that makes this relationship even more complicated: some Mexican leaders and parts of the educational bourgeoisie want to reconnect with the diaspora.
They want to use Mexican Americans as provisional “ambassadors” for Mexico, who represent their interests in the United States.
Let us tell our American colleagues how great a visit to this country is and put pressure on the political leadership to intensify their ties with Mexico.
Well, now.
That won't happen.
Too many hurt feelings.
And given the unfair distribution of income, unbridled corruption and drug violence, many of us are not so sure if it is really a great country.
I'm afraid you'll have to go through that alone, Amigos.
That's fair.
If at least some Mexicans are not yet willing to forgive the United States for dealing with Mexico a century and a half ago, they must also accept that some Mexican Americans have a grudge over how their family members were treated not so long ago.
- Hmmm.
Maybe we're more "Mexican" than I thought.
Old battles, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could prove to be an unexpected pillar of peace
Can there ever be a lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
The latest bloody events seem to stifle such hope in the bud.
In the midst of the usual blame, countless buildings have been smashed, more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis killed – and for the first time rockets from Gaza near the Israeli metropolis of Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem have been smashed.
But although Israelis and Palestinians seem trapped in their historical conflict, the Middle East is changing around them.
The Arab Spring has created a new, uncertain situation, and whether they want it or not – Palestinians and Israelis have become part of these turmoils.
Perhaps this will only lead to more bloodshed.
But there are reasons to believe that the deadly stalemate could finally come to an end.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, optimism seems far from appropriate in view of the current situation.
Even if the truce agreed on 21 November continues, this week’s fighting has strengthened the hard-fought on both sides.
The leader of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has controlled the Gaza Strip since 2007, will claim to have pushed the Israelis back, even though his group itself suffered major losses.
Although several Hamas leaders are killed and the 1.7 million inhabitants of the Gaza Strip are trapped in one of the most desolate and densely populated corners of the planet, Israel has so far failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is winning in the West Bank, controlled by the rival, moderate Palestinian group Fatah.
And the Hamas leaders may conclude that they have time on their side.
Just as Islamists have gained influence in the Arab world, Hamas has been able to attract powerful and rich friends to its side.
Turkey, a resurrected regional power once regarded as Israel’s closest Muslim ally, has taken over for the Hamas party – just like Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic Gulf states.
Rejoicing Hamas supporters believe that Israel is forming an Islamist crescent – from Lebanon in the north, where militant Hezbollah has the power, to Syria, where rebels of an increasingly Islamist prominence could face the overthrow of Bashar Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies threaten the king.
And in particular, the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under President Muhammad Mursi in Egypt – by far the most populous and most important Arab country – on the southern flank of Israel has changed the balance of the region sustainably.
Hosni Mubarak, the Laizist despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until its fall in 2011, had little time left for Hamas.
In contrast, the Brotherhood is weakened with Hamas and its leaders are more dependent on popular views.
In future diplomatic negotiations, Hamas could prove to be an actor that cannot even be pushed out by Israel and the United States.
The Israeli hardliners, on the other hand, draw an opposite conclusion.
From a military point of view, Hamas is no longer a threat.
The Israeli missile defense system, “Iron Dome”, has proven itself and many of Hamas’ missiles have been destroyed.
For at least a while, Israel will be able to sleep more quietly.
From a diplomatic point of view, the United States holds its position firmly, and many European countries have blamed Hamas for the latest escalations of violence.
Israel has been doing well in recent years, especially under Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets from the Gaza Strip have killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, the country has remained relatively free of suicide bombers - not least thanks to the barriers that run into the West Bank and thus into the main part of a possible Palestinian state, which protect the Jewish settlements, which have been declared illegal but are constantly being expanded.
Netanyahu’s Likud party has allied with an even more militant group in the run-up to the January 22 election under Avigdor Lieberman.
Why do these insidious Palestinians also mess around and leave their own state to them?
If they really had control of the West Bank, wouldn’t they, like their fellow Gazars, also fire rockets?
No, it is better to keep them in check behind the wall and punish them if they dare to lift their heads.
Perhaps the hardliners will be able to prevail, but the Arab Spring could make a difference to them.
Even if the Islamists, who are now in power in Egypt and other countries, have little left for Israel, they will initially focus on the difficulties in their own country.
Israel’s defense budget is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
A war with the local superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments to repair their economy.
That pragmatic President Mursi teamed up with Barack Obama to achieve a ceasefire could be a promising sign – and perhaps symbolize the beginning of a new era.
Israelis should also think more long-term.
While the rest of the Arab world is taking timid steps towards democratization, Palestinians are still deprived of their right to self-determination – a powder barrel that will undoubtedly one day explode in the Israeli-occupied territories, just as a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Suppression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state, and with the growth of the Arab population, this situation will only exacerbate.
Bloody missions to push back Hamas in the Gaza Strip will increasingly demand its diplomatic tribute over the years.
Both sides need a push from the outside
The correct answer is the one represented by the more reasonable representatives of both sides, the majority of the rest of the world, and by this newspaper: two states in which Israel resigns for security purposes.
The hope - small for the near future - is that the ceasefire will give more influence to outsiders in order to enforce this solution.
Egypt, together with Turkey and Qatar, must now stop arms shipments to the Gaza Strip and is better positioned than ever to convince Hamas of the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, supplemented by territorial exchanges and a common Jerusalem.
Foreign Arab nations should also push Hamas and Fatah to reach an agreement.
This would do more for the creation of a Palestinian state than with the imminent request for UN observer status.
Obama must also play his part in urging Israel to negotiate.
During his first term in office, he missed the idea of his own peace plan.
Far away in the White House, it seems as if he is also averse to participation.
But this is a regrettable, short-sighted perspective.
The United States has a significant interest in a stable Middle East.
This includes a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
Australian legislation on unified cigarette packaging comes into force
Health warnings and diseased body parts on neutral green packs that are the same for all tobacco brands
The world’s first single cigarette and tobacco packaging laws have come into force in Australia, replacing brand logos and colours with neutral, olive-green lids, which are also printed with drastic images showing sick body parts and infants and children suffering from cigarette smoke.
Apart from the different health warnings and images once, the only difference between the packs in the brand names, printed in identical, small fonts, is coming Saturday.
Australia is introducing the strictest regulations for tobacco packaging in the world.
The Australian government wants to stop young people from smoking by eliminating the glamorous picture of tobacco use.
The government assumes that studies have shown that people who have not yet started smoking at 26 years of age are 99% likely to stop smoking afterward.
"You can see from young children that they understand the message of trying to promote the tobacco companies with their brand image," says Federal Minister of Health Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that have shown, for example, that children associate the crown of a logo with the idea of a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and the changes will have a minor impact on the profits of multinational corporations, other countries are already considering similar steps.
The Tobacco Lobby fought hard against the laws.
It was said that the laws would favour black market trade, leading to cheaper and more accessible cigarettes.
“The laws will lead to serious, unintended consequences,” says Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Chinese and Indonesian counterfeiters will offer far larger quantities of these products on the streets of Australia.
Others, on the other hand, say that the laws have boosted their business.
