In a constantly electrified world, it’s nice to be bored sometimes.
This Thanksgiving I unexpectedly spent five hours at the airport when our plane was down due to mechanical problems and we had to wait for another plane.
So I had enough time to get bored with a few thoughts.
I don't want to lie.
Waiting half a day at the airport for a flight is quite annoying – even when books, magazines, and iPhones (and of course tax-free shopping) are available.
But more and more academics and child development experts are leading boredom as something positive.
When it comes to them, it’s okay for us — and our children — to get bored occasionally.
This forces the brain to lose itself in interesting thought processes, which may promote creativity.
And because most of us are staring almost constantly at one or the other screen these days, we no longer benefit from the benefits of boredom.
Should we welcome boredom with open arms?
Yeah, yeah.
And no.
I'll go back to that.
Like many people, I have always assumed that boredom is a relatively current phenomenon that has evolved with increasing leisure time.
But Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada and author of "Boredom: A Lively History" (Yale University Press, 2011), doesn't see it that way.
“In fact, boredom has a very long history,” he says.
Pompeii’s house walls adorn a Latin graffiti about boredom dating back to the first century.
And then there is the question of how we actually define boredom.
According to John D. Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at the University of York in Ontario, Canada, the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After long reading of research literature and presenting the idea in front of a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues concluded that boredom can be defined as the experience of wanting to do a satisfying job, but not being able to do it.
Boredom differs from apathy in that the person is not busy, but wants to be.
With apathy, however, there is no urge to do anything.
The key experience of boredom, he says, consists in a "disruption of the attention process, coupled with bad mood and the feeling that time is only passing slowly".
Boredom can sound almost like depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes that although these two conditions may be related, bored people see the problem in their environment or the world, while depressed people see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we’re bored, even if we’re just having trouble concentrating.
In her study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention" - in German for example: "The idle mind: The definition of boredom under the aspect of attention", published in September in the journal "Perspectives on Psychological Science", Professor Eastwood and his colleagues point to an earlier experiment, in which participants listened to a volume in front of which a person read a magazine article.
Some groups heard a loud television program from the neighboring room that had nothing to do with the content, others heard it at low volume, so it was hardly noticeable, while the third group did not hear these sounds at all.
The people who heard the barely audible television said they felt more boredom than the other two groups - they had problems concentrating, couldn't find a reason for this and attributed their difficulties to boredom.
Trying to focus on a difficult or strenuous task can lead to the disruption of attention to boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, if you do a monotonous job - "like searching for defective products on a factory conveyor belt, music can distract and help you not to feel bored".
In fact, he says, we now know that tangles and scribbles, often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can even fight them by keeping people more physically attentive.
"Studies have shown that children who are allowed to roll around are learning more and retaining more information than those who are forced to sit breastfeeding," Professor Fenske said.
We all get bored at some point – my late flight, a roaring loudspeaker, a particularly tiring film.
But some people get bored easier than others.
To measure these differences, researchers developed a "scale of boredom susceptibility" in the 1980s.
On the scale there are statements like "Many things I have to do repeat themselves and are monotonous" and "I have so many interests that I don't have enough time for everything".
Using such scales, researchers have found that boys are more likely to get bored than girls, according to Stephen Vodanovich, professor of psychology at the University of West Florida – particularly in terms of the need for more and a greater variety of external stimuli.
But in general, teens are a pretty tense bunch.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day with a pager.
He found that 32% of adolescents were bored at school and doing homework, while 23% said they were bored when they were not in school.
However, only 3% of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson says today, 21 years later, he doesn’t know if the percentages of boredom have increased or decreased.
However, he is sure that "youth is perceived as particularly boring", mainly because children and teenagers do not have much influence on their daily routine.
So back to my original question: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases it causes people to take on extreme physical risks and fall into gambling or drugs to alleviate them – studies have shown.
On the other hand, many philosophers and authors examine the relationship between boredom and creativity, and this is the opinion of Professor Vodanovich, who has been researching the subject for more than two decades.
"With boredom, the brain wants to tell you that you should do something else," said Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at the University of New York.
But the brain doesn’t always know what to do best.
If you are bored and you use this energy to play and cook guitar, you will be happy.
However, while television can provide happiness in the short term, it can escape in the long term.
So if you give your bored child an iPad, it can keep them from being bored, but it has not learned to entertain or control themselves, says Professor Fenske.
And he adds, "Self-control transfers from one situation to another."
The child not only learns to entertain, but also gains more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we should celebrate boredom.
Nor should we consider them too critical.
Instead, our goal should be to feel comfortable even outside of constant activity and technology.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"It sounds like we have to be bored more often, but boredom is the agonizing, incessant desire to do something meaningful," he says.
He believes that in truth people are only looking for a way to shut down and relax.
"In an environment where we are constantly overstimulated, it is difficult to deal with once the noise is silenced."
In Colorado, there is no clear guideline for the new marijuana law
The 19-year-old community college student and football player Anthony Orozco is facing a crime in southeastern Colorado that will soon be legal in that state: the possession of a few marijuana chunks and a pipe with which he smoked them.
According to Orozco, he and some friends were traveling by car in Lamar near the Kansas border on a September day when they were stopped.
After the police officer found marijuana in the car, Orozco was charged with possession of drugs and drug utensils — cavalry offenses, each with a $100 penalty — and received a court appointment.
"We are being treated like criminals," Orozco said.
But is he one too?
In the uncertain weeks following the state’s decision to legalize small amounts of marijuana for its own use, the answer to hundreds of smaller drug offences depends less on the law than on the site.
Hundreds of regulatory offences revolving around marijuana have already been dropped here and in the state of Washington, which approved similar measures.
The police authorities no longer prosecute adults over the age of 21 for possession to a small extent, which is permitted by law as soon as the new laws come into force in the next few weeks.
But prosecutors in Colorado’s more conservative districts have announced continuing to prosecute existing marijuana offenses and are still quoting people in court.
At the same time, several cities, from the Denver suburbs to the Western Mountains, are voting to prevent new, state-licensed marijuana stores from opening in their communities.
“This situation is evolving so fast that I don’t even know what’s going to happen next,” said Daniel J. Oates, head of police in Aurora, east of Denver.
Regulators in the state of Washington are also scratching their heads.
They are waiting for guidance on setting up a licensing system for the production, manufacture, distribution and sale of the drug - and have a deadline until 1 December 2013 in mind.
In Washington, it is believed that Colorado is ahead of most states when it comes to the regulation of marijuana, where the drug was first legalized for medical purposes and then for self-consumption.
“Colorado has a more regulated market, so the state is good for orientation,” said Brian E. Smith, spokesperson for the Washington State Spirits Authority.
But Smith also admits that no place or system can do more than serve in the sense of a rough guide.
"We don't have a real precedent that we can follow," he adds.
The Washington law, called I-502, comes into force on December 6th, forming the endpoint of a grey area in which the state licensing system does not yet exist, but possession is legalized.
And unpleasant practical issues need to be clarified during this time – for example, how to agree the state’s requirement of “appropriate access” to licensed marijuana with the banning of cannabis shops within 300 meters of schools, parks, playgrounds and childcare facilities.
“Nowhere will it be more difficult to find a location for a licensed cannabis business than in urban areas, especially in the Seattle metropolitan area,” said Ben Livingston, spokesman for the Center for Legal Cannabis, a recently formed research group.
On November 21, Chief Oates sent an e-mail to his employees in Aurora stating that the prosecutor would no longer prosecute minor marijuana offenses among individuals over the age of 21, and that the police would not seek "immediate" criminal charges for these offenses.
Chief Oates added that the police would continue to enforce urban regulations to regulate growers of medical marijuana and drug traffickers would continue to be prosecuted.
In Weld County in northern Colorado, District Attorney Ken Buck has a stricter view.
After the vote, he stated that his agency would continue to pursue cases of marijuana possession, mainly to move consumers to withdrawal.
Currently, 119 people have to face trial for possession of about 50 grams or less of marijuana, although many have also been charged with other crimes.
“Our agency has the duty to prosecute violations that were criminal offences at the time of the crime,” Buck said in a statement.
The reactions are even ambiguous in places like rural Mesa County, where voters rejected the marijuana initiative.
The police in Grand Junction, the largest city in the county, are no longer showing adults for possession of smaller quantities.
District Attorney Pete Hautzinger supported this decision, but also decided not to drop all pending possession procedures.
"I don't think I'm wasting my time trying to enforce the law until it changes," he says.
Although 55% of voters in Colorado supported the measure, it was clear from the outset that it would not be easy to reconcile the personal consumption of marijuana with the complexities of government and legal system.
And the contradictory reactions throughout the state have brought to light a deep rift among local officials with regard to the great green experiment.
District prosecutors are a “cultural barrier,” says Sean McAllister, a Denver-based lawyer who represents defendants on trial for marijuana offenses and acts locally as a spokesman for the national marijuana law reform organization.
"They have spent such a large part of their lives prosecuting people for still not being able to accept legalization," he believes.
As the first states to treat smaller amounts of marijuana like alcohol, Colorado and Washington are traded as national sample cases for the legalization of drugs.
While advocates and state officials are preparing for an era of legal sales, they are also nervously waiting for instructions from the federal government, which wants to continue to treat the sale and cultivation of marijuana at the federal level as a criminal offence.
Advocates of the legalization movement hope that the Ministry of Justice will yield.
Despite several eye-catching arrests of consumers and medical marijuana sellers, the federal government has allowed the sale of medical marijuana in Colorado, Washington and 16 other states.
Kevin A. Sabet, former Obama administration drug policy adviser, believes that while criminal officials will likely not enter doors to confiscate smaller amounts of drugs, they will probably resist tolerating legal, state-regulated marijuana deals under the new legislation.
Several cities in Colorado are not waiting for federal authorities to act.
Even before the election day, some local municipal authorities approved moratoriums on new marijuana stores, although they could only open in about a year.
Last week, Montrose, a city in the West, decided on a six-month ban, which is likely to be passed next week.
“We don’t want to get into a position where we license someone and then face a major problem at the federal level,” said Bob Nicholson, a member of the city council.
Our community voted against this change of law.
We focus on what the community has chosen and not on what the state has chosen.
Many questions are still open.
Petronella Wyatt: I was bullied from Oxford because I'm Tory
Not only today’s university students are being attacked for their views
It has always been my biggest dream to get a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother had attended that university, which I once considered to be the world’s greatest stamp of knowledge, for a modern Greek symposium that promoted the great pillars of civilization—free thinking and tolerance.
But within two weeks of moving to Worscester College at the end of the 1980s - there I had planned to study history - I had packed my bags again and thus brought about the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed in tears.
My friends were confused.
The Evening Standard said I had left because I had a problem with fellow students having sex in the neighboring room.
Author A. N. Wilson said that I had left university because I was forced to drink from damaged cups.
But the truth was less amusing.
I ran away.
Yes, I ran, because I was suffering from systematic bullying and threats.
Not because of my very unusual name, or because I came from a private school.
I had only been harassed for one reason - a reason that seemed all the more narrow and cruel in this supposed cradle of enlightenment: my now deceased father Woodrow Wyatt had been a major adviser to Margaret Thatcher and I was a supporter of the Conservative Party.
Why am I mentioning this right now?
Well, according to current reports, a new generation of students of the moderate right suffers from similar persecution.
The organized and rising hatred of Tory students in Oxford has now developed such dimensions that a group of them last week demanded the same level of equal rights protection that benefits gays, disabled people and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of Corpus Christi College's Junior Common Room (JCR) state they are "often actively isolated, personally assaulted and declared undesirable" due to their political views.
They demand a place on their college’s equality committee to ensure their opinions can be freely expressed.
Her situation was exacerbated by a recently aired documentary about political students on BBC Two, "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right", which portrayed Tories as eccentrics and neo-Nazis.
Among other things, it featured graduate Joe Cooke, former president of the Oxford University Conservative Student Association, who rode in a Rolls-Royce and wore a silver-colored suit and silver-studded walking stick.
At other universities, conservative students say they are regarded as "sincliners for introducing higher tuition fees."
20-year-old Luke Black, vice president of the Nottingham University Conservative Student Association, said in a Sunday newspaper: "There is a growing left-wing tendency in universities.
People think we're like the Bullingdon Club without even getting to know us."
Samuel Roberts, 21 and history student in Corpus Christi, who initiated the request for greater protection, believes such a climate is "unpleasant". 19-year-old Stephanie Cherill, designated president of the Conservative Student Association of Oxford, says she has observed a growing rejection of students of the moderate right among JCR members.
"This poses a threat to intellectual discourse and the well-being of members," she says.
During my first weeks in Oxford, I was one of such a minority.
As an incredibly shy 18-year-old, I arrived in September 1986.
The hatred of the Conservative Party had reached its peak.
Last year, the university had voted not to award an honorary degree to Margaret Thatcher - a former student - due to cuts in higher education.
The atmosphere would have even frightened Stalinists.
In the first days of the first semester week, when new students get to know each other and the tutors, I got a taste of the future events.
I had the experience that the tutors not only tolerated the ridicule of Tory students, but even took part with pleasure.
Political issues such as the miners’ strike, the privatization and the government’s rejection of sanctions against South Africa’s apartheid regime found their way into the wood-paneled rooms of the tutorium.
At my first of these events, I was supposed to translate French texts from the 18th century into English.
"Miss Wyatt," said tutor Harry Pitt (now deceased), "please translate the first paragraph."
I stumbled into it.
Pitt was a little man with a face like cake dough, and quite hated.
"Do Thatcher supporters refuse to learn French, or are they just stupid?" he asked.
The other students giggled.
In my eyes, tears swelled.
"I suggest they take a few French lessons in your spare time - so if you're not too busy with your social activities," Pitt murmured to me.
I returned to my room with my head hanging.
That evening, I was sitting alone in college at dinner, when someone slightly tapped me on my shoulder.
It was a second-year English student named James who introduced himself as a member of the Conservative Student Association.
"I know who you are," he said kindly.
Unfortunately, it is what it is.
Anyone suspected of being Tory is being harassed.
It's bad enough for me, but they know that your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it's gonna be worse for you.
Most Tory first semesters claim to be supporters of the Labour Party.
In a local pub, I later tried to adjust.
I insisted that I did not agree with Mrs. Thatcher on all points.
This trick should prove unsuccessful.
A freshman in philosophy, politics, and business who ironically attended Eton College, which was considered conservative, told me, "You're the daughter of a fascist pig."
You're dirty.
Other students shared his opinion.
I was perverted and dirty.
“How do Tories have sex?” one asked.
They beat each other, right?
I felt the same way homosexuals must have felt before the more liberal legislation of the United States.
Would I ever succeed in living a normal life at Oxford University?
Would I be able to meet like-minded people only after dark?
Should I turn to the Labour Party and have to suppress my natural inclinations?
The three years that were before me extended before my spiritual eye to a purgatory of fear and isolation.
The only tutor openly recognizing himself as Tory was Norman Stone, a professor of contemporary history who had his seat in my college.
He was hated not only for being a conservative, but also for advising Thatcher on foreign policy and writing speeches for her.
He was rarely there.
He hated the place, found it provincial and petty, and rejected it for his Marxist-determinist perspective on history.
In 1997 he accepted a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
“You won’t be happy here,” he told me.
I began to commute between Oxford and my parents’ house and found refuge with more open-minded friends and family members in the city.
I told my father that I hated Oxford, and why I did it.
He seemed incredulous.
During his time in the 1940s, all political views were accepted.
"But it's the best place in the world," he said.
They would never do such a thing, not in my city of dreaming towers.
Even my communist friends always displayed impeccable manners.
His damp eyes were clouding.
Give the whole thing a chance.
I'm sure they're just teasing you.
It would break my heart if you left.
Exhausted by my frequent travels to London, my emotional resistance weakened.
One of my male friends, also Tory supporters, had given in to the pressure and renounced his beliefs.
During a tutorial the following week, where another history tutor had seriously claimed that I was “an enemy of the people,” I decided to do the same.
Although I was secretly crushed with shame, I admitted that my parents had undergone "brainwashing," calling them "old bastards."
The relief lasted only a short time.
It was my father who slapped the last nail in the coffin of my Oxford career.
At that time, he wrote two columns a week in the Murdoch press.
My door was locked.
I hid in my room, and after five minutes my hazers gave up.
When they left, I packed a suitcase and took the first train to London.
I never returned.
You can call me a whiny slut.
But no 18-year-old should ever have to suffer from such intimidation and malice in an educational institution.
And even more tragically, it was Oxford – a university that not only produced 14 Tory Prime Ministers, but still hides behind an undeserved reputation of equality and freedom of thought.
