The most difficult profession in the world: the human work animals of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the bearers of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and their health when they carry 70 kilos of sulfur over the steep, rocky paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their lives by extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, he has to climb down to the bottom of his crater every day, where the sulphur-containing gas flowing out of the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After breaking out large sulfur stones, which can weigh up to 70 kilos in total, he transports them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders across the sloping paths of stone.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to a height of 2386 meters, but the exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb at the turtle pace, keeping the balance and carefully taking their steps so that they do not slip and crash.
They know that every step can cost their lives, as happened to a French tourist who crashed years ago on the steep slopes of the Kawah Ijen.
The Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 cents for every kilogram of sulfur they extract.
Once at the top, they pave the way between the tourists who photograph them like circus monkeys and walk three kilometers with the tiresomely heavy baskets to the scale, which a mining company has set up a little further down at an altitude of 1850 meters
The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, who has been exploiting the volcano’s deposits since 1960 and (no better yet) its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 eurocents) for each kilogram of sulfur.
She then sells this for 10,000 rupees (83 Eurocent) to the petrochemical industry, because this mineral is widely used in everyday life and is used for the production of matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even for bleaching sugar.
"Since we normally carry 70 kg, we get about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each route," explains Anto, who normally makes three runs a day.
It takes three hours for each track, after which it is completely done, but at the end of the day it has 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) together.
What looks like a miserable wage for such a seemingly inhuman effort, however, is three times what he would earn with the field work.
"The daily wage of the miners here, where the coffee harvest pays 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) a day and the average monthly income is two million rupees (167 euros), is very high," explains the carrier, who previously worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There he earned 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day, and the work was not so hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a nearby village, for a reason as important as sulfur in Indonesia: "I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I took her to Java to convert her to Islam".
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated because of the toxic gases.
