Héctor "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
The basketball globetrotter, Héctor "Hetin" Reyes, has been associated with basket sports for more than 60 years and has travelled the world.
Few in Puerto Rico have such a large intellectual collection of the history of the country's basketball as Héctor "Hetin" Reyes.
Before being tied to the wheelchair by a stroke in 2008, Rexes was part of this sport for 6 years, whether as a lower-class player, player of the first national league, proxy and leader in the BSN with the Vaqueros de Bayam<0xC3><0xB3>n or president of the Basketball Association.
"For my entire life, I have put on many hats in basketball, even several at the same time, when I was president of the BSN, chief executive of the national team and president of the association in the 1990s," Reyes recalled on a visit from Primera Hora to his home in Bayam<0xC3><0xB3>n, where he lives with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
"Basketball was my life."
Reyes does not exaggerate with this statement.
The walls of his house are almost all decorated with photos and memories of his long career and testify to them.
Bayam<0xC3><0xB3>n in the heart
The most emotional memories are those reminiscent of his time with the Vaqueros from the mid-1950s as a player until 1982, where he celebrated his 15th anniversary as co-director or managing director of the club.
“These were my best years I have enjoyed the most because I was allowed to be part of eight Vaqueros championships since 1967, be it as managing director, co-manager or coach.
There were many fulfilling years, including the five championships successively from 1971 to 1975.
And then I said goodbye with a 1981 championship, the year of Jerome Mincy’s debut at BSN.
From then on, "Cuco" took over Ortiz, who was a very good manager," Reyes says.
I remember Gene Bartow, who worked here as a coach and was employed at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), telling me, “I have a very strong and 2m tall player.
Do you want him?"
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico has ever had.
Bartow then recommended free throw specialist Raymond Gausse, who became a native and was one of our best throwers.
I remember how he said that if Mincy had allowed a championship for Bayamon, Gausse would provide another.
The Vaqueros Championship with Gausse was granted to him, but already from a distance, because he was already at the top of the association in 1988.
At that time he preferred to enjoy his executions and Mincy's in the national team.
I remember when we won the US for the first time at the pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico.
Then came the 1990 World Cup, where we took fourth place, which should have been bronze if it had not been that Canadian referee who let us repeat the last turn for the second time, Reyes said.
Was this 1990 World Cup group the best national team you’ve ever seen?
She is one of the best, as was the one who won the 2004 Olympics against the Dream Team.
My favorite is the team of the 1991 Pan American Games in Cuba, where we won gold and offered the team of the USA a fight, as they did when they won bronze against us at the World Cup.
Not only Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico L<0xC3><0xB3>pez and "Picul<0xC3><0xAD>n" (Ortiz), but also the young players (Javier) "To<0xC3><0xB1>ito" Col<0xC3><0xB3>n and James Carter, the brothers Le<0xC3><0xB3>n (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who could not be there in 1990 due to a knee injury.
A team that was perhaps not the best in terms of personalities, but with which we won a gold medal and which gave us great pleasure was that of the 1995 pre-Olympic tournament in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and the young Rolando Hourruitiner as a substitute for the blocked players because of the events at the Pan-American Games in Mar del Plata, we won the gold medal against any prediction.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
That was without a doubt Picul<0xC3><0xAD>n Ortiz.
His numbers at the level of international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated this level as much as Picul<0xC3><0xAD>n.
And this without considering his career in the different leagues he played in.
Who was the best coach in Puerto Rico?
This is a difficult question.
We had a number of good coaches like Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
I like the work of Leo Arill.
What do you think is the best thing you have achieved in the association?
I was part of the most successful era of the national team from 1988 to 1995, which included the BSN at the beginning of the 90s up to 17 teams in a season.
What else do you have to do?
