I'm proud of that.
What are you doing today?
I like to listen to music, watch videos of music of my time on YouTube, enjoy my grandchildren and occasionally go to a basketball game.
And of course I enjoy the company of my wife Isabel, who was always by my side.
Larry Hagman is dead.
Larry Hagman was born on September 21, 1931 in Forth Worth, Texas, and became famous worldwide with his role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R." in the television series "Dallas", where he played a ruthless, insidious and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as oil magnate J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of the greed of the 80s, is dead.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in a new season of "Dallas", died Friday afternoon due to cancer complications, according to a family press release to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., producer of "Dallas".
"Larry was back in his beloved hometown of Dallas, where he once again played the iconic role he liked the most," the family said.
Larry's family and his closest friends were with him in Dallas for the Thanksgiving celebrations.
Linda Gray, who played the role of his wife in the original and follow-up series, was with Hagman when he died at the Dallas hospital, her publicist Jeffrey Lane said.
He made everyone who knew him happy.
He was creative, generous, funny, funny, loving and talented, and I will miss him very much.
"He was an original person and lived life to the fullest," Gray said in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with cirrhosis in 1992, and he admitted to drinking a lot over the years.
In 1995, a malignant tumor was found in his liver, and he underwent a transplant.
In the years before "Dallas", Hagman became known on television as a nice guy in the years 1965 to 1970 with the sitcom "Bezaubernde Jeannie" of the television station NBC.
There he played the astronaut Tony Nelson, whose life is turned upside down when he meets an attractive "Jinn" (played by Barbara Eden) who will live with him at home.
He has also starred in two short-lived comedies, such as The Good Life (NBC, 1971-72) and Here We Go Again (ABC, 1973).
His cinematic work included critically acclaimed roles in "The Group", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was his masterful interpretation of the enchantingly detestable J.R. that made Hagman a superstar.
The dramatic series of the CBS television chain about the Ewing clan and other characters in its surroundings was broadcast from April 1978 to May 1991.
The advertising slogan "Who shot J.R.?", which was supposed to create the expectation for an episode full of emotions where Hagmann's figure was almost killed, led to an international speculation, and millions of dollars were wagered in betting houses.
The series reached a record for spectators at that time.
When the answer became known in a chapter in November 1990, it was seen by an average of 41 million viewers who turned "Dallas" into the second most watched entertainment program since the end of "MASH" in 1983, which had 50 million viewers.
It was Kristin, the sister-in-law of J.R. (interpreted by Mary Crosby) who had shot.
J.R. had impregnated her and threatened to portray her as a prostitute if she did not leave the city, but others also had reasons for wanting to see him dead.
Hagman interpreted the role of Ewing as a corrupt, insatiable man with a charismatic smile: a sneaky businessman and unfaithful husband who sought to enlist his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray).
"I know what should be on J.R.'s tombstone," Hagman said in 1988.
It should be called "Here rests the honourable citizen J.R. Ewing".
This is the only business he hasn’t won.
Victoria Principal, co-actress of the original series, recalled on Friday Hagman as an "enormous personality on and off the screen".
He is unforgettable and irreplaceable to millions of worshippers in the world and remains in our hearts for those of us who have had the good fortune to know and love him.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" were broadcast a few months ago with great success on the TV channel TNT.
The recording of five chapters for the second season was completed, and a sixth chapter was just shot, the station informed.
Warner or TNT did not immediately explain how Hagmann’s loss would be handled in the series.
Born in Fort Worth, Texas, he was the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who played classical works such as "South Pacific" and "Peter Pan".
Martin was still a teenager when she got Larry during her marriage to lawyer Ben Hagman.
He tried his luck on the theater stages in New York in the early 1950s, after which he served in the Air Forces in England from 1952 to 1956.
There he met the young designer Maj Axelsson and married her.
The couple had two children, Preston and Heidi, and they lived for a long time in the California city of Malibu, where many celebrities reside.
In 2001, he titled his memoir "Hello Darlin: Tall (and Absolutely True) Tales about My Life".
"I didn't write anything that I believed could harm someone or harm them in any way," the Associated Press said at the time.
After the liver transplant, he campaigned for liver donations and worked as a volunteer in a hospital to assist anxious patients.
"I advise them, give them courage, I'll meet with them when their operations are imminent and after that," he said in 1996.
I want to give them some comfort, such as "don't worry, it's a bit uncomfortable the first time, but you'll be fine".
He also campaigned against smoking and took part in several campaigns.
Beginning of the course that studies the "end of the world"
Each week, students explore apocalyptic issues such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
Every semester, when the religious professor decided to take a course on the end of the world, he knew he had an irresistible fishing hook: the end of the Mayan calendar’s “long back count” on December 21, which many people believed meant the end of the world.
But Charmé had no idea what to expect in the next two months: the destructive hurricane Sandy, which some have referred to as “Dedarmaggedon,” as well as a growing conflict involving Israel, the place Christian theorists believe the apocalypse is beginning.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester ever," Charmé told students at Rutgers-Camden University, New Jersey, this week.
If someone analyzes what happened in the world today, as if we were thirty days away from it, this would be a really good period.
And he reminds us that the bad is good for those with an apocalyptic mentality.
And he’s not the only professor to offer courses on the “end of the world” this semester, which should actually be the last in history.
In Temple, Professor Barry Vacker gives the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World."
Each week, students explore apocalyptic issues such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
“We analyze why these ideas spread over time,” he said, as well as the way hypothetical scenarios are offered that lead to a particular human behavior.
For example, if nuclear material gets into the hands of terrorists, a war could break out.
This month, the students analyzed films with apocalyptic content and examined how they compare to real life.
“I tried to inform students about what is possible, likely, credible, and impossible,” Vacker said.
On the main campus of the University of Pennsylvania, Professor of Latin American History Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an associate professor of art history and anthropology, formed a team to offer a course called "The End of the World."
“We’re not taking 2012 so we always have the option to hold the course again in case the world doesn’t go down,” Restall said.
Despite the "imminent downfall", students must study, create projects and take final exams.
In Penn State, the final exam is held on the eve of the apocalypse, so students have no other chance than "to continue working until night, where the world is supposed to end," Restall said.
The courses were very popular.
"In two hours, there were no more seats," Restall said of his course for high-average students, which filled with 35 students.
For weeks before the start of the semester, we received emails from students asking if there were still seats available.
The students themselves assure that the course is among the most interesting.
"It's fascinating to see what people are doing to comfort themselves," said Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student in Rutgers's Camden for Religion and Sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey.
The apocalyptic sect or religious mentality is actually only a matter of consolation or its absence.
The 25-year-old student Will Wekesa for psychology and nursing explains that he has seen all the apocalyptic films.
"I've never heard of a lesson where this is taught," he said.
I enjoy it.
But none of the students surveyed—and less so a professor—explained to believe in the last date of December 21.
“Our first project dealt with the prophecy of the Mayans, and in certain ways we discredit them,” said Julie Zeglen, a student last year in Temple, 21 years old and from West Chester.
The Mayans never predicted the end of the world; it’s just a key point in the calendar, Restall said.
However, he notes that in Western society there is an apocalyptic fear that goes back several centuries when people reacted to changes in their environment by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has increased this speculation.
“People don’t think that way elsewhere,” he says.
This is mainly the case in the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at the University of La Salle, who teaches in the Philippines this year, quickly answers the question of whether he would know there a course about the "end of the world".
“The Philippines does not participate at the end of the world,” he wrote in an injunction to an exception to a higher instance.
We have a pardon from the Pope.
Restall pointed out that over the years many days have been spoken by the last court, saying that if nothing happens on December 21, "people immediately think of a new date" or philosophize that December 21 is the beginning of a seven-year period after which the end of the world will come.
Students and professors take this date easy.
Several said they wanted to go to celebrations about “the end of the world.”
“Maybe I’ll call a few friends so we can laugh together,” said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
